<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Wants To Investigate Mars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Britain wants to send a space probe to Mars in  
2003 to investigate whether there is life on the red planet, the 
government said Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The spacecraft will be named Beagle Two -- after the ship that  
carried Charles Darwin on his 1830s voyage that shaped his theory 
of evolution. It will be emblazoned with the Union Jack. 
</P>
<P>
	A spokesman from the Department of Trade and Industry said the  
probe would be launched from the European Space Agency's Mars 
Express satellite, due to take off in 2003. 
</P>
<P>
	``Beagle Two is a probe that will detach itself from the  
satellite and go down to the surface of Mars, where its purpose is 
to examine the elements present to see if life could have existed, 
did exist or could appear in the future,'' the government spokesman 
said, speaking with customary anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1996, a team of scientists in America caused an uproar with  
their announcement that a meteorite from Mars showed evidence of 
ancient microfossil life. Since then, researchers have raised 
serious doubt about the conclusions that primitive biological life 
existed on Mars 4 billion years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Independent analyses have failed to yield absolute evidence that  
the potato-sized chunk of rock, found in Antarctica in 1984, ever 
contained life. 
</P>
<P>
	The British project, which is expected to cost $40 million, was  
to be announced by Science Minister Lord Sainsbury this week, The 
Sunday Times reported. The London-based newspaper said much of the 
money had already been raised by universities and industry. The 
government was expected to meet any shortfall, The Times said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
