<DOCNO> APW19990801.0027 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 15:40:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Columbus 4, Miami 0 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) -- Stern John scored three goals Sunday to  
power the Columbus Crew over the Miami Fusion 4-0 in a Major League 
Soccer game. 
</P>
<P>
	With the win, Columbus snapped Miami's four-game winning streak  
to close within four points of first-place D.C. United. 
</P>
<P>
	John got the fourth hat trick of his career with goals in the  
12th, 83rd and 90th minutes to move into third place in MLS scoring 
with 28 points. 
</P>
<P>
	Columbus substitute Brian West had two assists after entering  
the game in the 60th minute. 
</P>
<P>
	John's first goal came off assists by Jeff Cunningham and John  
DeBrito. Then in the second half, West stole the ball at midfield, 
dribbled down the left sideline and sent a rolling pass just past 
diving goalkeeper Garth Lagerwey to John, who scored from 6 yards 
out. 
</P>
<P>
	John got his first hat trick of the season in the final minute  
off a cross by West. Robert Warzycha also assisted on the play. 
</P>
<P>
	Columbus (13-7) dominated the game, outshooting Miami 19-8 and  
12-3 in shots on goal. 
</P>
<P>
	Miami's best chance came in the 65th minute when Jay Heaps'  
volley from 18 yards out was deflected inside the box, but 
Columbus' defense recovered to clear the ball. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990801.0028 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 15:00:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 6 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Four Die in Ohio Plane Crash  
</P>
<P>
	NORTH LIMA, Ohio (AP) -- A single-engine plane crashed in a  
cornfield just after taking off from an Ohio airfield today, 
killing at least four of the five people aboard, authorities said. 
The fifth person on the Piper was hospitalized. The crash occurred 
in North Lima, about 66 miles southeast of Cleveland. 

</P>
<P>
	Kosovo Tension High After Explosion  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Peacekeepers scrambled to keep a lid  
on simmering ethnic tensions after a bomb damaged a Serbian 
Orthodox church under construction in Kosovo's capital today. The 
early morning blast did little damage to the structure, but it 
further undermined the already weak confidence of minority Serbs in 
the ability of the Western alliance's KFOR peacekeeping force to 
protect them from violence. 

</P>
<P>
	Algeria Vote on Peace Plan Set  
</P>
<P>
	ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) -- Algeria will hold a referendum Sept. 16  
on a peace plan intended to end a seven-year Islamic insurgency, 
officials said today. The so-called ``civil concord'' plan for 
national reconciliation includes a large amnesty and the reduction 
of prison terms for militants not guilty of murder, rape or 
planting a bomb. President Abdelaziz Bouteflika has said he will 
resign if his plan, already approved by the country's parliament 
and senate, is rejected by the Algerian people. 

</P>
<P>
	Rains in S.Korea Kill At Least 10  
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- Rescue workers in dinghies and  
helicopters plucked stranded residents from flooded homes today 
after two days of torrential rains that left at least 10 people 
dead. The downpours forced more than 11,380 people to flee 
submerged homes between the South Korean capital of Seoul and the 
border with North Korea, government disaster officials said. Two 
people were missing. 

</P>
<P>
	9 Cops Killed in Colombia Attack  
</P>
<P>
	BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- Hundreds of leftist rebels launched a  
three-day attack on a police station with homemade missiles and 
automatic weapons, killing at least nine officers and destroying 
nearby homes and businesses, police said today. Eight police were 
wounded, and 11 more feared taken prisoner in the weekend attack, 
which ended today. Leftist Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia 
on Friday began ravaging the small town of Narino, 100 miles 
northwest of Bogota in the state of Antioquia. 

</P>
<P>
	Indonesia Results To Be Announced  
</P>
<P>
	JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) -- Results from Indonesia's first open  
parliamentary election in more than four decades are to be 
announced tomorrow after a watchdog committee threw out allegations 
of irregularities in the poll. The Election Watch Committee 
rejected about 100,000 irregularities cited by small parties that 
had refused to accept results from the June 7 parliamentary poll. 

</P>
<P>
	Democrats, GOP Split on Tax Package  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republicans determined to pass $792 billion in  
tax cuts met stiff opposition today from Democrats and the White 
House making the case against cuts of any size. ``We are much 
further apart than the public understands,'' said Sen. Phil Gramm, 
R-Texas. GOP and Democratic moderates still held out hope for a 
compromise that would give Americans a tax cut over the next 
decade. But one moderate, Sen. John Chafee, R-R.I., said there was 
a good chance neither side would get what it wanted. 

</P>
<P>
	English Cops Can Use Plastic Bullets  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Police in England and Wales today were given the  
right in serious rioting to use plastic bullets -- controversial 
ammunition that has killed 17 people in Northern Ireland during 
three decades of sectarian violence. Plastic bullets, known as 
baton rounds, have never been used in England and Wales. Police 
authorities also announced stricter rules for using the bullets in 
Northern Ireland. The same rules will apply in England and Wales. 

</P>
<P>
	'Runaway Bride' Tops 'Blair Witch'  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- ``Runaway Bride,'' starring Julia Roberts and  
Richard Gere, debuted atop the weekend box office, according to 
estimates today. ``The Blair Witch Project,'' the summer's 
low-budget surprise, came in second with $28.5 million in its first 
weekend of wide release. 

</P>
