<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Volker Sets World Backstroke Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ISTANBUL, Turkey (AP) -- Germany's Sandra Volker broke her world  
record in the 50-meter backstroke at the European Swimming 
Championships on Sunday, and Pieter Van den Hoogenband of the 
Netherlands emerged as the new star of the meet. 
</P>
<P>
	Volker was first off the blocks to finish in 28.71 seconds and  
defeat Spain's Nina Jivanevskaia (29.02). Metka Sparavec of 
Slovenia got the bronze in 29.25. Volker broke her mark of 28.78 
last month in Monte Carlo. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know myself where I got the power from for this world  
record,'' Volker said. ``All the races seem to have drained me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Holland's Pieter Van den Hoogenband defeated world and European  
champion Alexander Popov of Russia, swimming the 50-meter freestyle 
in 22.06. The Russian left the pool with his first bronze medal, 
behind Italy's Lorenzo Vismara. Vismara was second in 22.21 while 
Popov clocked 22.32. 
</P>
<P>
	Hoogenband has been unbeatable so far, delivering fast  
performances in every one of the five events he has entered. 
Holland's disqualification in the 800 relay Saturday robbed him of 
the fastest relay leg of all time in 1:45.20. 
</P>
<P>
	Runaway record breaker Inge de Bruijn took her 50-meter  
freestyle race in 24.99. Therese Alshammar of Sweden was second in 
25.30 and Alison Sheppard of Britain was third in 25.33. 
</P>
<P>
	Marcel Wouda, another star in the new Dutch swimming powerhouse,  
goes for gold in the 400 medley. But he faces tough competition 
from Italy's Alessio Boggiatto, Spain's Frederik Hviid, and 
Germany's Jirka Letzin. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dutch pair of Kirsten Vlieghuis and Cara Geurts are favored  
in the 400-meter women's freestyle, with their main competition 
coming from Camelia Potec of Romania. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 200-meter women's butterfly, Denmark goes for its first  
medal with Mette Jacobsen, who swims against Katrin Jaeke of 
Germany and Spain's Maria Pelaez. 
</P>
<P>
	The 11-day meet ends with the men and women's 400 medley relays.  
There also will be finals in women's 10-meter synchronized diving 
and the men's 3-meter springboard. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
