<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 13:30:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nothstein Wins Record 3 Cycling Golds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WINNIPEG, Manitoba (AP) -- Marty Nothstein got his hat trick.  
</P>
<P>
	The 1996 Olympic silver medalist in cycling set his goal at the  
Pan American Games as winning three gold medals, a feat never 
achieved in his sport. He took the match sprint, Olympic spring and 
Keirin events. 
</P>
<P>
	``I fulfilled my goal of winning three gold medals and  
dominating in winning those three events,'' said Nothstein, of 
Trexlertown, Pa., who has won four world titles and 15 national 
championships. ``The only thing better than this would be to repeat 
this feat in Sydney next year.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Nothstein, 28, won twice Saturday night. He teamed with Marcelo  
Arrue of Woodland Hills, Calif., and Johnny Bairos of Redlands, 
Calif., in the Olympic sprint to defeat Cuba. His third gold came 
in the Keirin, a seven-lap race that is motorpaced for the first 4 1/2 
laps. 
</P>
<P>
	``By winning three golds, I made history,'' Nothstein said. ``I  
think we showed people that the United States is a power in the 
sport of track cycling.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In all, the Americans have won eight gold medals, six silver and  
one bronze, their best Pan Ams showing. And there still are four 
events to go in cycling. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *ANOTHER NO-HITTER:* Ho-hum. Another shutout, another no-hitter.  
</P>
<P>
	Lisa Fernandez's gem late Saturday night in the U.S. women's 5-0  
softball victory over Cuba featured 15 strikeouts. She walked one 
batter, in the fourth inning. 
</P>
<P>
	The unbeaten world champions allowed a total of four hits in  
their first four games, with Danielle Henderson opening the Pan Am 
competition with a perfect game. 
</P>
<P>
	``Obviously I'm disappointed I walked someone,'' said  
Ferndandez, of Long Beach, Calif., and generally considered the 
best pitcher in the world. ``When you get in that situation and 
your team is up by four runs, you hate to give someone a free pass. 
I think that was the downer of the whole game.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *MEDALS RETURNED:* Three bronze medals were stolen from the  
Canadian men's water polo team -- and then returned. 
</P>
<P>
	After taking the bronze on Friday, team members were celebrating  
in a downtown Winnipeg restaurant. Their vehicle was broken into 
and personal belongings, including the three medals, were taken. 
</P>
<P>
	The medals, belonging to Garrett Head, Zoltan Csepregi and Alex  
Thibeault, were returned Sunday, however. Winnipeg police learned 
they were in a mailbox near the Winnipeg Convention Centre, and 
with the help of the Canadian postal service, the medals were 
retrieved. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *CLOSING CEREMONY UPHEAVAL:* A new configuration for the stage  
at the Pan Am Games closing ceremony next Sunday has forced 
thousands of fans to exhange their tickets. 
</P>
<P>
	Kim Browning, vice president of ticket sales for the games, said  
the new stage placement for the Guess Who, which is reuniting for 
the ceremony, dropped the seating capacity by 3,500 to 24,000. 
Anyone in sections affected by the new logistics must exchange 
their tickets for different seats. Organizers said those fans also 
will have better views from their new seats. 
</P>
<P>
	But organizers said they could not reach ticket holders who did  
not buy by credit card, except by advertising the changes through 
the media. Anyone attending the closing ceremony with a ticket in 
the blocked-off sections will automatically be switched once they 
get to Winnipeg Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *FAVORITE SON:* The folks in Okmulgee, Okla., have a special  
interest in the Pan Am Games. 
</P>
<P>
	Their favorite son, Kermit Holmes, is playing for the U.S. men's  
basketball team, and they're doing all they can to keep tabs on 
him. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're keeping up with me every day,'' said Holmes, who plays  
for the CBA's Quad City Thunder. ``They're on line, they're reading 
the papers. They're eating this up right now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A former Oklahoma University player, Holmes hasn't forgotten his  
roots. He goes back home during the offseason and runs a camp for 
youngsters every summer. He had 181 campers this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm proud to be from there,'' Holmes said. ``I've been living  
there for 30 years. I still stay there with my mom. My grandmother 
lives on First Street and we live on Third Street. So it's a small 
community. I'm representing them up here also.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Holmes has spent his entire seven-year pro career in the CBA.  
But he has seen a bit of the world during those years and still 
marvels at the opportunities that have come his way, even if the 
NBA hasn't been one of them. 
</P>
<P>
	He has played in Spain, South America, Puerto Rico and Turkey  
and now he's in Winnipeg. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't explain the joy,'' Holmes said. ``Every day I say to  
myself, if I'm in Winnipeg or on my way back from Istanbul or 
Uruguay, `I'm from Okmulgee, Oklahoma, and it's been a heck of a 
ride.' '' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
