<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> French Olympic Champion Panzo Dies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT-DE-FRANCE, Martinique (AP) -- Olympic sprinter Hermann  
Panzo, who won a bronze medal for France at the 1980 Games in 
Moscow, has died at the age of 41. 
</P>
<P>
	Panzo died Friday in a Fort-de-France hospital, apparently from  
complications from a stroke and heart attack he suffered last week, 
local media reported Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
	Panzo, a Martinique native, won the bronze as part of a French  
four-man 100-meter relay team in the 1980 Games. 
</P>
<P>
	``With Hermann's death, we've lost not only a great athlete but  
also a symbol,'' Alain Rousselin, former Martinique Athletic League 
president, said Saturday on Radio Caraibes International. 
</P>
<P>
	Panzo ended his Olympic career after the 1984 Games in Los  
Angeles and worked as a technical counselor for Martinique's sports 
department. 
</P>
<P>
	He is survived by his wife and three children.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
