<DOCNO> APW19990801.0039 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 13:20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bates Right at Home With Bears </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PLATTEVILLE, Wis. (AP) -- Making the jump to the NFL was easier  
for D'Wayne Bates than most rookies. 
</P>
<P>
	There were no horror stories about him getting lost when he  
arrived in a new city. He didn't have to find a new place to live. 
When it was time for practice, all he had to do was drive a couple 
of miles up the road. 
</P>
<P>
	After four years at Northwestern, Chicago is Bates' home almost  
as much as his hometown of Aiken, S.C., is. And since South 
Carolina doesn't really have its own football team, getting drafted 
by the Bears was about as perfect as it could get. 
</P>
<P>
	``I really have grown to love Chicago,'' he said. ``I was happy  
I got the chance to stay here. It's a great city, a great city for 
football.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bates and the Bears are hoping he has the same kind of success  
in the NFL as he had at Northwestern, where he's the all-time 
leader in receptions (210), yards (3,370) and touchdowns (26). In 
1995, he helped lead the Wildcats to the Rose Bowl, and had 145 
yards on seven catches against Southern California. 
</P>
<P>
	But Bates found out pretty quickly that the NFL is a long way  
from the Big Ten. 
</P>
<P>
	``My first minicamp, it took me awhile to adjust, especially  
speed,'' he said. ``Everybody on the field is an athlete, and you 
just can't run by anybody. You've got to come out here at the top 
of your game every day, every play. You take one play off and you 
get taken out just like that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bates is finding ways to stand out, though. He's had impressive  
catches each day in practice, including one that drew cheers from 
the otherwise quiet spectators. 
</P>
<P>
	He's also developing a reputation as one of the most mature  
rookies. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm extremely pleased with what speed he has, I'm pleased with  
his catching ability, I'm pleased with his athletic ability,'' 
receivers coach Mike Borich said. ``But what I'm most impressed 
with is his mind and what he sees. The way he can communicate and 
the decisions he can make so quickly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That's because Bates sometimes knows exactly what the  
quarterback is thinking. No, he doesn't have a psychic business 
going on the side. Before he became a standout receiver at 
Northwestern, he was a star quarterback in South Carolina. 
</P>
<P>
	He threw for over 1,000 yards and 11 touchdowns as a high school  
senior, and rushed for another 580 yards and 11 TDs. He was the 
county player of the year and an all-state selection. 
</P>
<P>
	``We seem to say it about D'Wayne all the time because it's  
true: He's consistent, he's smart, he's in the right place at the 
right time,'' Jauron said. 
</P>
<P>
	He isn't perfect, though. He needs to increase his yardage after  
a catch, Jauron said, lowering his pads and turning the ball 
upfield before he runs. And Bates said he wants to get more precise 
in his routes, like teammate Curtis Conway. 
</P>
<P>
	So he watches Conway in practice and on film -- just like he did  
a few years ago. When he made the switch to receiver in college, 
Bates studied hours of tape of Conway and his favorite player, 
Jerry Rice, and tried to emulate them on the field. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm just trying to gain all the knowledge I can right now,''  
Bates said. ``Now I can make my own name, and that's my goal.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990801.0040 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 10:20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Senate Passes Tax Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republicans pushed their $792 billion tax cut  
through the Senate on Friday, courting a classic veto struggle this 
fall with President Clinton and Democrats who claim the measure 
shortchanges Medicare and other domestic programs. 
</P>
<P>
	The vote was 57-43 -- largely along party lines -- in favor of the  
GOP plan. The 10-year measure includes broad-based tax relief as 
well as provisions designed to address the so-called marriage 
penalty and make it easier to accumulate retirement savings and pay 
for education. 
</P>
<P>
	Passage was followed by the beginning of efforts at forging a  
quick House-Senate compromise. Congressional GOP leaders hope to 
speed the final measure through both houses next week, although it 
won't be sent to Clinton until after Labor Day. 
</P>
<P>
	That would leave time for the GOP rank and file to trumpet the  
benefits of tax cuts during Congress' long August break. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want to cut taxes and the president wants to spend it,''  
Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., said of projected 
federal surpluses. ``That's what this fighting is all about. We are 
determined to give working Americans the tax relief they are 
entitled to.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton wasted little time renewing his oft-stated veto threat.  
``The Republican tax cut is so large it would undo our fiscal 
discipline and imperil our prosperity,'' he said in a written 
statement. ``It would crowd out our commitments to pay down the 
debt, to save Social Security and to strengthen and modernize 
Medicare with a long overdue prescription drug benefit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Senate measure includes a reduction from 15 percent to 14  
percent in the lowest personal income tax bracket, effective in 
2001. Beginning in 2006, it would gradually shift some income 
currently taxed at 28 percent into that lower bracket. 
</P>
<P>
	It also includes provisions to reduce the marriage penalty, in  
part by slowly raising the standard deduction for married couples 
to double the amount allowed for individuals. Individuals currently 
may claim $4,300, and couples $7,200. 
</P>
<P>
	Moments before final passage, the measure was amended to let  
investors exclude from taxes the first $1,000 in long-term capital 
gains. 
</P>
<P>
	Under the bill, more students would be allowed to deduct the  
interest on their education loans; limits on deductible 
contributions to individual retirement accounts would rise 
gradually to $5,000, and there would be liberalized tax incentives 
for individual and corporate donors to charities. 
</P>
<P>
	The bill also would create a new deduction for the cost of  
long-term care insurance, and raise the estate tax exemption -- 
already scheduled to increase to $1 million -- up to $1.5 million in 
2007. 
</P>
<P>
	Throughout three days of debate on the Senate floor, Republicans  
said their budget would set aside the vast bulk of projected 
surpluses for Social Security. The tax cuts, they stressed, would 
consume less than 24 cents of each dollar of predicted surpluses. 
</P>
<P>
	``It helps the family and it helps the country,'' said Sen.  
William V. Roth, R-Del., chairman of the Finance Committee and 
architect of the legislation. 
</P>
<P>
	But Democrats and the president contended the GOP bill would dip  
into Social Security surpluses beginning in 2005, and leave little 
or nothing for other domestic programs. They also said that by 
providing tax cuts based on economic forecasts that might not 
materialize, the Republicans were risking a return to the days of 
large federal deficits. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is another riverboat gamble with the American economy,''  
said Sen. Byron Dorgan, D-N.D., in an echo of the rhetoric used in 
the early 1980s when Republicans cut taxes. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats countered with a smaller tax cut of $290 billion,  
which was rejected earlier in the week. Efforts to fashion a 
bipartisan compromise at $500 billion collapsed Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	A final compromise is still a possibility at year's end, but the  
immediate prospect is for a veto confrontation driven by competing 
readings of the electorate's wishes 15 months before the next 
elections. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans, who called their measure the Taxpayer Refund Act of  
1999, hope they can force Clinton to bend to their wishes on tax 
cuts, and say the president and other Democrats will pay a 
political price otherwise. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats, meanwhile, believe they can frame the debate as a  
choice between risky, overlarge tax cuts on one side, and the fate 
of Medicare and other politically popular programs on the other. 
</P>
<P>
	Throughout the three days of floor debate, both sides sought to  
shore up potential weaknesses in their position. For their part, 
Republicans parried Democratic claims about Medicare by pledging to 
address the issue of prescription drugs this fall. 
</P>
<P>
	Democrats abandoned Clinton's initial approach of targeted tax  
relief in favor of broad-based tax cuts, although on a far smaller 
scale than the GOP wanted. 
</P>
<P>
	With an eye on the 2000 elections, when eight first-term  
Republican senators will seek new terms, Democrats forced a series 
of politically charged votes, including one on a proposal to reduce 
the tax cut to make room for prescription drug benefits for 
Medicare recipients. The amendment failed. 
</P>
<P>
	On final passage, the bill was supported by 52 Republicans, Sen.  
Bob Smith, I-N.H., and Democrats Mary Landrieu and John Breaux of 
Louisiana, Bob Kerrey of Nebraska and Robert Torricelli of New 
Jersey. In opposition, there were 43 Democrats and two Republicans, 
George Voinovich of Ohio and Arlen Specter of Pennsylvania. 
</P>
<P>
	At a news conference, Lott and House Speaker Dennis Hastert,  
R-Ill., outlined an ambitious schedule that calls for a compromise 
by Tuesday, with final votes in the two chambers by the end of next 
week. 
</P>
<P>
	There are numerous differences between the bills. One is a  
House-passed provision that calls for a 10 percent across-the-board 
income tax cut rather than the reduced income tax bracket the 
Senate approved. 
</P>
<P>
	Lott told reporters ``there's a lot of support'' among Senate  
Republicans for an across-the-board cut, adding, ``That is the 
fairest.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It will fall to Lott and Hastert to prod the chairmen of the  
tax-writing committees, Roth and Rep. Bill Archer, R-Texas, to 
avoid prolonged haggling that would slow the broader GOP political 
strategy. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990801.0041 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 23:10:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Grapefruit Industry Rebounding </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAKELAND, Fla. (AP) -- Florida growers and processors are  
remaking the image of the grapefruit, long the poor stepchild of 
citrus, by touting its health benefits and improving the tangy 
taste of its juice. 
</P>
<P>
	The makeover has been a big success so far, helping the  
grapefruit industry's sagging demand rebound steadily in the last 
two years. 
</P>
<P>
	Growers are getting their best prices since the mid-1990s and  
more people are drinking the juice and eating fresh grapefruit. The 
demand has bounced back so sharply that citrus officials say there 
could be a shortage between now and the start of the next growing 
season in November. 
</P>
<P>
	The Harvard Business School plans to use the grapefruit's  
comeback as a case study of how to turn around a struggling 
agricultural commodity. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's rare for an industry to turn around this quickly,  
especially one that is based on a tree crop and is planted in the 
ground for so many years,'' said Harvard professor Ray Goldberg. 
</P>
<P>
	It's a stark contrast from recent years when growers left fruit  
on trees to rot, dumped excess fruit in pastures for cows to eat 
and yanked out thousands of trees as prices plunged to their lowest 
levels in 35 years. The industry's governing body, the Florida 
Citrus Commission, considered restricting the amount of grapefruit 
grown to help prop up prices. 
</P>
<P>
	Florida supplies about half of the grapefruit eaten in the world  
and more than three-fourths of the grapefruit consumed in the 
United States. Last season, growers produced an estimated 47 
million 85-pound boxes. 
</P>
<P>
	About 60 percent of Florida's grapefruit crop goes for juice.  
</P>
<P>
	As a result, as goes grapefruit juice consumption so goes the  
rest of industry. Efforts to turn around the moribund grapefruit 
sector focused on getting more people to drink the juice. 
</P>
<P>
	One change made by processors about three years ago was to  
increase the juice's natural sugar content, known as brix, by 
paying growers more for sweeter grapefruit. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've gone from putting out what was a tart and tangy product  
and made it more palatable to the consumer,'' said Vero Beach 
grower Dan Richey, a citrus commission member. ``We're putting out 
a much better juice product. Better flavor. Higher quality.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Even more important was the marketing campaign by the Florida  
Department of Citrus and juice producers. 
</P>
<P>
	The department's $18 million ``Healthy Heart'' campaign was  
launched three years ago to tout grapefruit juice as free of fat 
and cholesterol. Television commercials, such as one showing a 
grapefruit beating like a heart, were aired around the country. 
Labels that said ``Certified Heart Healthy'' were placed on 
grapefruit juice cartons. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was a powerful, powerful motivator for the consumer,'' said  
Daniel Santangelo, the citrus department's executive director. 
</P>
<P>
	Grapefruit juice sales now are at their highest levels in a  
decade, 58.5 million gallons, after bottoming out in 1995 at 45.8 
million gallons. 
</P>
<P>
	The number of grapefruit juice drinkers, however, still pales  
when compared with orange juice consumers because far fewer people 
like the taste of grapefruit. 
</P>
<P>
	So far this year, U.S. grocery stores have sold about $3.1  
billion of orange juice but only $247 million of grapefruit juice, 
according to the citrus department. 
</P>
<P>
	The department will focus its advertising campaign next season  
on women aged 35 to 54 with a household income of $50,000 or more. 
To that end, it plans a promotional tie-in with the Lifetime cable 
channel, whose audience is predominantly female. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
