<DOCNO> APW19990801.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 17:10:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> PBS To Halt Donor List Exchanges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PASADENA, Calif. (AP) -- PBS stations will halt all exchanges of  
donor lists with partisan groups within a week, but when the 
political fallout for public broadcasting might end is difficult to 
predict, PBS president Ervin S. Duggan said Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``By the end of this week, no station in America will be engaged  
in these practices,'' Duggan told a meeting of the Television 
Critics Association. 
</P>
<P>
	``It has delayed the (federal budget) authorization process and  
I don't know what the outcome will be,'' he said. ``I hope we can 
put it behind us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Of the 349 public television stations nationwide, PBS has  
admitted that as many as 30 appear to have engaged in list rentals 
or exchanges with political groups. 
</P>
<P>
	At issue is whether the list-swapping constitutes a violation of  
federal tax law. Tax experts have said that such exchanges would 
not be a violation as long as all political parties receives equal 
access to the lists. 
</P>
<P>
	The issue came to light in May, when Boston station WGBH-TV  
admitted giving a list of donors' names to the Democratic National 
Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Although he condemned the practice, Duggan said outside list  
brokers working for PBS stations swapped names with both Republican 
and Democratic groups. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is nonpolitical and nonpartisan behavior,'' Duggan said,  
noting that Bob Dole's 1996 presidential campaign and the 
conservative think tank Heritage Foundation were among those 
involved in swaps. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked if the issue was being used by PBS critics as a weapon  
against public broadcasting, he replied carefully. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not going to deal with the motives of people on Capitol  
Hill or what might seem to some an effort to expand this issue 
beyond its proper limits,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal funding could be withheld from stations -- which get 25  
percent of their money from direct-mail appeals -- but that would be 
an overreaction because it was clear they intended to cooperate, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	In Washington, the House Commerce Committee was scheduled to  
consider funding for the Corporation for Public Broadcasting on 
July 14 but postponed the meeting after the mailing list 
disclosures. 
</P>
<P>
	Two lawmakers -- Rep. Billy Tauzin, R-La., chairman of the  
committee's telecommunications subcommittee, and Rep. Christopher 
Cox, R-Calif. -- have asked for investigations into the practice. 
</P>
<P>
	Tauzin, who was sponsoring the funding authorization bill for  
PBS, said he will reduce his funding proposal. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
