<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> It's a Proud Day for Elder Geiberger  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARK CITY, Utah (AP) -- No, Senior PGA Tour veteran Al Geiberger  
didn't win the Novell Utah Showdown. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, he sure looked and felt like the champion. That's because  
his son, Brent Geiberger, earned his first PGA Tour victory Sunday 
at the Greater Hartford Open. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's like winning, the adrenaline, the feeling,'' said the  
proud papa, flushed with excitement after coming off the 18th 
green. ``Of course, it's two different things. It's probably the 
only way I can still win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The elder Geiberger, winner of the 1966 PGA Championship and 10  
other tournaments, learned of his son's victory as he stood on the 
seventh tee box. He traded high fives with playing partners Howard 
Twitty and Jimmy Powell. 
</P>
<P>
	``I went down the fairway feeling like I had won the  
tournament,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Geiberger finished off the pace in Park City, shooting a  
final-round 71 that left him at 211, 5-under for the 54-hole 
tournament. 
</P>
<P>
	But in many ways, Al Geiberger looked like he had won, judging  
by the way he was cheered after news of Brent's victory was posted 
on the scoreboard and by the 45 minutes he spent in the press tent 
after his round. 
</P>
<P>
	Geiberger said he felt plenty of pressure, just not his own.  
</P>
<P>
	``It was tough,'' he said. ``Here I was out on the course  
playing my round and I'm pretending that I'm on the course there 
with Brent. I thought maybe I could take some of the pressure off 
him that way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Geiberger said his son had caddied for him several times on the  
Senior PGA Tour, and many of the other players in Utah offered him 
their congratulations. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm just very happy for Brent. Everybody that sees me out here  
is happy for us, too,'' Al Geiberger said. 
</P>
<P>
	Geiberger said Brent has always been a sound golfer, and it was  
just a matter of time before he collected his first victory as a 
professional. The times when Brent worked his dad's bag on the 
Senior Tour paid off. 
</P>
<P>
	``I always told him, 'You'll get just as many good breaks as  
bad, but if the bad breaks get you down, you'll never see the good 
ones,''' Al Geiberger said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
