<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Unlikely Teen Faces Murder Charge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- As a 10-year-old boy, Jason Meeks pleaded with the  
governor to ``stop the violence.'' Now a teenager, he is facing a 
murder charge in the death of another teen. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1991, Meeks wrote to then-Gov. William Weld, asking him to  
help clean up the city's Roxbury neighborhood. 
</P>
<P>
	``Make the people that are selling drugs go to school and put  
the bad people in jail,'' Meeks wrote. The letter prompted Weld to 
visit him at school in 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	Meeks, now 18, was arrested Friday. He is accused of shooting  
another teenager, Tari Thomas, in May 1998, The Boston Globe 
reported Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Thomas was shot once in the head, said Suffolk District Attorney  
Ralph C. Martin II. 
</P>
<P>
	In March, Meeks was arraigned on a gun possession charge and  
freed on $2,500 bail. The charge is still pending. 
</P>
<P>
	A relative of Meeks who requested anonymity told the Globe that  
Jason's mother, Shirley Hicks, died about two years ago. His 
mother's death deeply affected Jason, the relative said. 
</P>
<P>
	``His mother was his best friend,'' the relative said. ``He and  
she were real close. It still kind of bothers him just like anybody 
else who loses their mother.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
