<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 12:50:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Reds Happy To See Guzman Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CINCINNATI (AP) -- As the trading deadline approached, Greg  
Vaughn wasn't sure what the Cincinnati Reds were going to do. 
</P>
<P>
	Would they add a starting pitcher to their already over-budget  
roster to improve their playoff chances? Or would they trade away a 
high-priced veteran -- someone like him? 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't rule out anything,'' Vaughn said Sunday. ``When you're  
hitting .230, anything's possible.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The rebuilding Reds made a statement with the way they wound up  
trading late Saturday night. By getting starter Juan Guzman from 
Baltimore for two minor leaguers, they showed they want to win now 
as well as later. 
</P>
<P>
	``The organization made a commitment because it had to take on  
some salary,'' Vaughn said. ``That tells us they're going to go as 
far as they can to help us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Reds got an undisclosed amount of cash from the Orioles to  
help pay the remainder of Guzman's $5.25 million salary. It's the 
second time they've gone over budget this year to get a player they 
wanted. 
</P>
<P>
	The acquisition of Vaughn in the offseason pushed the payroll to  
$33 million on opening day. The trade for Guzman adds a little 
more. 
</P>
<P>
	Although the Reds are rebuilding for 2003 when their new stadium  
opens, they've decided to put a little more money on the line to 
stay in contention now. 
</P>
<P>
	The players were delighted. Third baseman Aaron Boone walked up  
to managing executive John Allen in the clubhouse Sunday morning, 
shook his hand and pumped his fist. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's great, man,'' team captain Barry Larkin said. ``It  
addresses a need. Everybody in here has to feel very good about 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``When you have a chance to do it now, sometimes you've got to  
pull the strings and do it now. That's the way baseball is,'' 
pitcher Denny Neagle said. ``I was glad to see it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There was some apprehension in the clubhouse the last few days  
because teams had been asking for at least one of the Reds' young 
pitchers in a deal. General manager Jim Bowden refused and wound up 
sending minor leaguers B.J. Ryan and Jacobo Sequea to the Orioles 
for Guzman and cash. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am very impressed that we could get him without getting rid  
of anybody on the ballclub,'' catcher Eddie Taubensee said. ``It 
was a very intelligent move.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It was a move the Reds felt they had to make stay in contention  
in the NL Central, where they've been in first or second place 
since June 17. Their rotation is a mess. 
</P>
<P>
	Steve Parris went on the disabled list Sunday with a strained  
right triceps. Pete Harnisch has been pitching with a sore shoulder 
that might need surgery at the end of the season. Steve Avery went 
on the disabled list a week ago. Ron Villone and Brett Tomko have 
been erratic. 
</P>
<P>
	Although the Reds' bullpen has the lowest earned run average in  
the major leagues, it has pitched the second-most innings in the 
majors because the starters are averaging only 5.5 innings. 
</P>
<P>
	This couldn't go on.  
</P>
<P>
	``Steve is on the disabled list and Pete's going out and giving  
us what he has, but you don't know if it's a situation you can go 
the whole year with,'' pitching coach Don Gullett said. ``And 
there's no logical choice at the minor league level.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Guzman was 5-9 with a 4.18 ERA in 21 starts for the Orioles.  
He's averaging 5.8 innings per start, was tied for the American 
League lead with 65 walks in 122 2-3 innings and will be a free 
agent after the season. 
</P>
<P>
	Guzman, 32, led the AL with a 2.93 ERA in 1996, but was on the  
disabled list six times from 1995-97 because of a muscle imbalance 
in his shoulder, a sore armpit, a strained chest muscle, an 
emergency appendectomy, a broken thumb and a strained shoulder. 
</P>
<P>
	``The first time I faced him, I was in awe of him,'' said center  
fielder Mike Cameron, who played for the Chicago White Sox. ``I 
faced him when he was well. He was nasty.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Given the state of the rotation, he doesn't have to be nasty to  
help the Reds. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're getting a pitcher who can give us innings we desperately  
need,'' Bowden said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
