<TEXT>
<P>
	White House Touts Workfare Success  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The White House said today that all 50 states  
have moved the required number of people from welfare to work, 
noting that 35 percent of the nation's welfare recipients held jobs 
in 1998. The president plans to promote those numbers on Tuesday at 
a welfare-to-work conference in Chicago, and use them to make the 
case for Congress to provide funding for services, such as child 
care, to aid the welfare-to-work transition. 

</P>
<P>
	Chinese Army: Ready To Squash Plots  
</P>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- China's army, the world's largest, marked its  
72nd birthday today with warnings to both Taiwan and an outlawed 
meditation group that it was ready to ``smash any plot to split the 
nation.'' Defense Minister Chi Haotian repeated the government's 
accusations that Taiwanese President Lee Teng-hui last month had 
gone further down the ``dangerous road of splitting the 
motherland'' in suggesting that China and Taiwan deal with each 
other as separate states. 

</P>
<P>
	Farmers Cheer End of Brit Beef Ban  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- With open-invitation barbecues, British farmers  
celebrated today the lifting of a three-year ban on British beef 
exports imposed by European regulators after an outbreak of mad cow 
disease. But there is a long way to go to regain markets and try to 
re-establish confidence that British beef is safe, particularly in 
other European countries. The embargo crippled Britain's beef 
industry, which lost an estimated $2.4 billion in sales. 

</P>
<P>
