<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 9 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Arafat Tries To Unite Palestinians  
</P>
<P>
	CAIRO, Egypt (AP) -- In a bid to unite Palestinian ranks before a  
new round of peace negotiations, PLO chairman leader Yasser Arafat 
met today with an extremist group that has opposed peace deals with 
Israel. Arafat held talks with representatives of the Popular Front 
for the Liberation of Palestine, whose leader had refused to meet 
with the chairman until he admits that the revocation of the 
Palestine National Charter was a mistake. The Palestinians in 
November formally rescinded parts of the charter, which called for 
the destruction of Israel. 

</P>
<P>
	Blast Damages Serb Church in Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- A large explosion damaged a Serbian  
Orthodox Church under construction in the heart of Kosovo's capital 
early today, the latest sign of ethnic hatred threatening the 
province's fragile stability. Tensions over the presence of Russian 
peacekeepers in Kosovo also have risen sharply after the Russians 
yesterday briefly detained a top commander of the Kosovo Liberation 
Army, chief of staff Agim Ceku. If such actions aren't stopped, 
ethnic Albanian rebel leader Hashim Thaci warned, ``We will defend 
our honor.'' No one was injured in the explosion at the Sveti Spasa 
church. 

</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Clinton Discusses Husband's Weakness  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- First lady Hillary Rodham Clinton, answering  
questions about her husband's affair with former White House intern 
Monica Lewinsky and the scandal that followed, said his actions 
were ``a sin of weakness, not a sin of malice.'' Mrs. Clinton 
defended President Clinton as ``a very, very good man'' but said, 
``Yes, he has weaknesses, yes he needs to be more responsible, more 
disciplined,'' she told ``Talk'' magazine, according to a news 
release from the magazine yesterday. ``I thought this was resolved 
ten years ago. ... I thought he had conquered it,'' she said of the 
president's infidelity. 

</P>
<P>
	Heat Wave Death Toll Reaches 150  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- While some parts of the nation saw temperatures  
drop yesterday, the death toll stemming from the recent heat wave 
continued to climb. The heat has been blamed for 150 deaths 
nationwide since July 19. An additional 20 deaths in Chicago may be 
heat-related and were under investigation, Mayor Richard Daley 
said, announcing the latest deaths from the heat wave that scorched 
much of the nation and produced New York City's hottest July on 
record. 

</P>
<P>
	Heat May Have Had Role in Fatal Crash  
</P>
<P>
	COTTRELLVILLE TOWNSHIP, Mich. (AP) -- Federal investigators say  
heat may have been a factor in the plane crash that killed nine 
skydivers and a pilot yesterday. The National Transportation Safety 
Board says hot weather and high humidity can make takeoff more 
difficult. Yesterday was in the 80s and humid. The plane, a 
twin-engine Beech King Air 200, came down in a grassy field near 
Marine City Airport, about 40 miles north of Detroit, police said. 

</P>
