<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 9 Deals As Trading Deadline Passes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Chuck Finley dreamed about going from last place to first in one  
day. The Philadelphia Phillies were hoping to add Andy Pettitte. 
The Tampa Bay Devil Rays appeared finally ready to join the trading 
frenzy. 
</P>
<P>
	As baseball's trade deadline passed Saturday at midnight EDT,  
the trades that weren't made were more notable than the ones that 
were. 
</P>
<P>
	Not that there weren't any trades. They just didn't involve the  
big names that were sent packing last July 31, like Randy Johnson, 
Todd Stottlemyre and Todd Zeile. 
</P>
<P>
	There were nine trades pulled off Saturday, including three by  
the New York Mets and two by the Oakland Athletics. 
</P>
<P>
	``We weren't supposed to be here in July,'' A's general manager  
Billy Beane said. ``Now we're trying to make our mark in this 
race.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Beane did that by overhauling his pitching staff in the last  
week in preparation for a wild-card run. The A's got Kevin Appier 
from the Kansas City Royals and also sent Billy Taylor to the New 
York Mets for pitchers Jason Isringhausen and Greg McMichael. 
</P>
<P>
	Those two deals came after trades that sent ace Kenny Rogers to  
the Mets and brought in starter Omar Olivares and infielder Randy 
Velarde from Anaheim. 
</P>
<P>
	The Mets were the busiest team. Besides acquiring Taylor from  
Oakland, they got outfielder Darryl Hamilton and left-hander Chuck 
McElroy from Colorado and infielder Shawon Dunston from St. Louis 
for outfielder Brian McRae and three minor leaguers. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going for it,'' GM Steve Phillips said. ``Now's the  
time. You don't know how many times the opportunity will present 
itself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Perhaps the most surprising player not to change addresses was  
Finley. The noted Yankees killer, who is 16-9 against New York in 
his career, had been rumored all month to be ticketed to Cleveland 
-- or even the Yankees in a defensive move. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead of jumping into the middle of the pennant race, Finley  
stays in Anaheim, far behind Texas in the AL West. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's easy to get teased watching Cleveland and the Yankees and  
those teams swing away, but I tried to be realistic,'' Finley said. 
``I'm not disappointed that I'm still here, I'm not disappointed 
that I'm not there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Yankees had backed out by the end. And some even questioned  
whether they were really even involved at all, or were just in the 
talks to drive up the price for their October rival. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's the same thing that happened last year,'' Blue Jays GM  
Gord Ash said. ``New York's wants to do what Cleveland is thinking 
of doing and Cleveland wants to do what New York is thinking of 
doing but neither one wind up doing anything.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cleveland ended up doing nothing to bolster a pitching staff  
that is seventh-best in the AL. Despite efforts by Indians GM John 
Hart, Cleveland enters the stretch run without a starter whose ERA 
is under 4.00. 
</P>
<P>
	``If the right guy was out there for us, we would have done  
something, believe me,'' Hart said. ``We kept looking for that top 
line pitcher.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That pitcher wasn't out there. Appier and Baltimore's Juan  
Guzman -- who went to Cincinnati -- were the top starters to change 
teams. 
</P>
<P>
	The Yankees weren't shut out of the deadline dealing completely.  
They reacquired postseason hero Jim Leyritz from the San Diego 
Padres for a minor league pitcher. 
</P>
<P>
	The Yankees didn't deal Pettitte, who has struggled for most of  
the past year and drawn ire from owner George Steinbrenner for not 
being aggressive on the mound. 
</P>
<P>
	The Phillies were hoping to add Pettitte to their pitching  
staff. But the Yankees apparently cooled at the idea late Saturday 
when they couldn't acquire Tampa Bay reliever Roberto Hernandez 
despite talks into the final hour. 
</P>
<P>
	The Devil Rays, who also couldn't deal Rolando Arrojo or Fred  
McGriff, insisted on top prospect Alfonso Soriano being included in 
any deal with New York. Tampa Bay has made only three deals in more 
than 20 months since the expansion draft. 
</P>
<P>
	Trades still can be made, but players must first pass through  
waivers. That means any club can step in and block a potential 
deal. Teams might be a bit more wary to block a deal this year 
after watching San Diego get stuck with Randy Myers' hefty 
contract. 
</P>
<P>
	Three division leaders -- Cleveland, Texas and Houston -- made no  
moves heading into the deadline. That's not always a bad thing. 
Last year's pennant winners, the Yankees and Padres, both stood pat 
a year ago. 
</P>
<P>
	The Atlanta Braves, beset by injuries, did make a last-minute  
deal, acquiring left-hander Terry Mulholland and infielder Jose 
Hernandez from the Cubs for three minor leaguers. 
</P>
<P>
	The Braves, facing their first pennant race in six years,  
learned last week that they had lost catcher Javy Lopez and starter 
Odalis Perez for the season. That comes on top of earlier injuries 
to first baseman Andres Galarraga and closer Kerry Ligtenberg. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you lose offensive production like we have with Galarraga  
and Lopez, it's hurtful,'' GM John Schuerholz said. ``I don't mean 
to suggest that Hernandez will replace that. But it will give us 
another weapon offensively.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990801.0059 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 12:20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Two Cubs Find Time's Up in Chicago </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Jose Hernandez's wife Melanie had set the  
microwave timer for 11 p.m. CDT Saturday night. If they did not 
receive a phone call before the timer went off, they were staying 
in Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
	The timer buzzed as the trading deadline struck. Less than two  
seconds later, their phone rang. 
</P>
<P>
	Hernandez and pitcher Terry Mulholland were dealt to the Atlanta  
Braves for 24-year-old left-hander Micah Bowie, 20-year-old 
right-hander Ruben Quevedo and a player to be named. Bowie will 
start Tuesday against the Montreal Expos. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think this was an opportunity to acquire two starting  
pitchers,'' Cubs general manager Ed Lynch said. ``It just so 
happens that they are young players. When you have a chance to 
acquire two young starting pitchers, you do it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mulholland and Hernandez packed their gear Sunday and said  
goodbye to their teammates. Hernandez's son, Jose Jr., was dressed 
in his Cubs jersey and wore a Cubs cap. 
</P>
<P>
	``My wife was already celebrating at home,'' Hernandez said of  
Melanie, who switched from cheers to tears at the news. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cubs had tried to keep Hernandez, 30, offering him a  
three-year deal, but Hernandez's agent wanted more money and four 
years. 
</P>
<P>
	``I got into an argument with my wife when I got home after  
yesterday's game,'' Hernandez said. ``I didn't know what to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And now?  
</P>
<P>
	``We've got to move along,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Mulholland, 36, is used to moving. He's played for five teams in  
t seven years, and bought moving boxes earlier in the week. 
</P>
<P>
	``Actually, it was a surprise,'' said Mulholland, who was 6-6  
with a 5.15 ERA. ``I really believed that after last year, we'd do 
bigger and better things. I still believe these guys are capable of 
playing well. It kind of twists in my gut that I'm not a part of 
it. On the plus side, I'll be with Atlanta. It's a mixed emotion 
thing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He planned on driving to Pittsburgh to join the Braves and  
report on Tuesday, dropping off personal belongings at his parents 
home in Uniontown, Pa., along the way. 
</P>
<P>
	Mulholland was scheduled to start Sunday but rookie Kyle  
Farnsworth started in his place. 
</P>
<P>
	Chicago recalled infielder Jose Nieves from Triple-A Iowa, and  
he will see the most playing time at shortstop, manager Jim 
Riggleman said. Nieves, 24, was batting .268 with 25 doubles, 11 
homers and 59 RBI and was a participant in the Triple-A All-Star 
game. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cubs also placed reliever Rick Aguilera on the disabled list  
because of a left calf strain and recalled left-handed reliever 
Steve Rain from Iowa. Rain pitched in 40 games for Double-A West 
Tenn earlier this year and was 3-1 with 24 saves and a 1.59 ERA. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
