<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Packers' Brooks Misses Practice Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREEN BAY, Wis. (AP) -- Wide receiver Robert Brooks was missing  
from practice again Sunday at the Green Bay Packers training camp 
amid speculation that he could be considering retirement. 
</P>
<P>
	After participating in the Packers' first full-squad workouts  
Friday, Brooks, 29, was given Saturday off by coach Ray Rhodes. 
</P>
<P>
	``My understanding is he's got a couple days to sit back and  
think about it and let Ray or Ron know what he's going to do,'' 
offensive coordinator Sherm Lewis said. 
</P>
<P>
	Rhodes said after the Sunday morning practice that he planned on  
speaking with Brooks later in the day. But Rhodes said later Sunday 
that did not happen and he now expected to talk to the player 
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Brooks has said in the past he would retire if he was not  
completely healthy. 
</P>
<P>
	Brooks ``has certainly earned the opportunity to make up his own  
mind, and let's not speculate as to what it is he's going to do,'' 
Packers general manager Ron Wolf said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Let's let him make this decision rather than play this what-if  
game. And when he does, then we'll know what we're going to do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wolf said that, if Brooks does retire, he believes the team can  
replace him with one of its younger receivers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have the utmost confidence in our ability to develop  
receivers,'' Wolf said. ``It's something we've always done here and 
I think we'll continue to do that. And we have some very talented 
people who are involved in that. So, I'm not concerned with that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With Brooks and holdout split end Antonio Freeman both absent  
Sunday morning, Bill Schroeder and Derrick Mayes worked with the 
first team while Corey Bradford and Jahine Arnold worked with the 
second team. 
</P>
<P>
	Schroeder, 28, is coming off his most productive pro season,  
with 31 receptions for 452 yards in 13 games. But his season ended 
when he broke his collarbone in three places Dec. 7 against Tampa 
Bay. 
</P>
<P>
	Mayes, 25, has been plagued by injuries since the Packers picked  
him in the second round of the 1996 draft. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradford, 23, who played just one year of college football at  
Jackson State, had three regular-season catches in eight games last 
year. But he did haul in a 47-yard bomb from quarterback Brett 
Favre in the Packers' playoff loss to San Francisco, and Lewis said 
during the offseason minicamps that Bradford could be the No. 3 
receiver this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Brooks underwent surgery during training camp last year to  
repair a herniated disc in his back. 
</P>
<P>
	He did not practice again until Oct. 11. He played in the first  
five regular-season games. 
</P>
<P>
	The injury bothered him throughout the season, and he finished  
with 31 catches for 420 yards and three touchdowns, having been 
inactive for four games late in the season. 
</P>
<P>
	Brooks had the same surgery in January amid talk that he might  
retire. He agreed to a $1.1 million pay cut in June, which the 
Packers said eased their salary-cap restriction. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
