<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Starr's Probers Asked About Sex </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Webster Hubbell, a longtime friend of  
President Clinton and Hillary Rodham Clinton, says investigators 
for Independent Counsel Kenneth Starr questioned him about the 
couple's sex lives as well as his own. 
</P>
<P>
	Starr's aides seemed especially interested in speculation  
involving Mrs. Clinton and White House lawyer Vincent Foster, who 
died of a gunshot wound in 1993, Hubbell said in an interview in 
this week's issue of The New Yorker magazine. 
</P>
<P>
	The questioning came as part of Starr's inquiry into the death,  
he said. Starr concurred with earlier findings that Foster 
committed suicide. 
</P>
<P>
	The article quoted a spokesperson for Starr's office as saying  
the investigators ``at all time asked relevant and proper 
questions. A professional and thorough suicide investigation always 
focuses on motives.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hubbell, a former associate attorney general, did not return a  
call from The Associated Press seeking comment. 
</P>
<P>
	He served 16 months in prison after pleading guilty to charges  
of bilking the Rose Law Firm in Little Rock, Ark., where Mrs. 
Clinton and Foster also worked, and its clients out of several 
hundred thousand dollars. 
</P>
<P>
	He now is on a year's probation for a negotiated guilty plea to  
tax evasion. 
</P>
<P>
	Prosecutors ``wanted to know about Hillary's sex life. About the  
president's sex life, and mine, too. They specifically asked if 
Hillary and Vince had had an affair,'' The New Yorker article 
quoted him as saying. 
</P>
<P>
	``I was surprised. For one thing, I think it's awful personal.  
And I don't think it's anybody's business,'' he added. 
</P>
<P>
	Hubbell said prosecutors asked him detailed questions about  
whether he had extramarital sexual relationships with specific 
women, and he denied any affairs. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
