<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chelsea Worked at Cattle Ranch </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LEWISTOWN, Mont. (AP) -- Chelsea Clinton worked part of the  
summer as an intern at a Montana cattle ranch, weighing bulls and 
sorting breeding pairs, before being called home early following 
the disappearance of John F. Kennedy Jr. 
</P>
<P>
	The N-Bar Ranch in central Montana has an intern program for  
college students interested in agriculture. Chelsea had taken a 
course in environmental economics at Stanford University. 
</P>
<P>
	``She was a delight,'' said ranch owner Susan Allred. ``She just  
pitched right in and worked with everyone else.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The president's daughter started in June, and plans had been for  
her to stay six weeks. But she was called back early to Washington 
by her father on July 17 -- the day Kennedy's plane disappeared. 
</P>
<P>
	Chelsea spent her time at the ranch helping move cattle, sorting  
pairs, weighing bulls, assisting with embryo transfers and 
collecting biocontrol insects. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
