<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 15:20:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cancer Doesn't Slow Panthers' Coach </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SPARTANBURG, S.C. (AP) -- With temperatures near 100 degrees and  
no shade anywhere, the practice fields at training camp would seem 
like the last place a cancer patient would want to be. 
</P>
<P>
	Don Breaux, the tight ends coach of the Carolina Panthers,  
doesn't see it that way. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is what I love. This is where I belong,'' he said. ``I  
feel like I need to be here.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He had colon cancer surgery in May and was at the team's  
minicamp three weeks later. These days, he has chemotherapy every 
Friday, and he's on the job full time. 
</P>
<P>
	While the trainers tend to overheated players and fans in the  
sweltering heat at Wofford College, Breaux refuses to complain. 
</P>
<P>
	Wearing gray shorts, a white T-shirt and a blue baseball cap to  
cover his thick crop of white hair, Breaux cheerfully ambles around 
the three-field complex. He jokes and laughs as he offers advice to 
his tight ends and coaxes other players. 
</P>
<P>
	``The man is incredible, just incredible. I don't know how else  
to describe it,'' tight end Luther Broughton said. ``We tell him 
all the time he should take a couple days off, but he just keeps 
smiling, saying he's OK and all that. 
</P>
<P>
	``It sure puts all this football stuff in perspective. You think  
you've got it tough in the heat and everything, and then you see 
him all happy and acting like he doesn't have a care in the 
world.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this year, Breaux was about to have surgery on his  
chronically sore back. Then his blood tests showed something that 
drew concern. Further exams led to the discovery of a cancerous 
colon. 
</P>
<P>
	Breaux, 59, had cancer surgery after minicamp in May. By the  
next minicamp in June, he was back on the field. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's no problem, really. Some days I feel a little better than  
others, but they tell me I'm cured, so I believe them and just go 
on from there,'' he said. ``I have great faith. It's not like I had 
to manufacture faith just for this situation. I have great faith, 
and it's held me up to this point.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Doctors say his best chance of keeping the cancer from returning  
is a precautionary round of chemotherapy. 
</P>
<P>
	In true Breaux fashion, he gets his chemotherapy on Fridays  
because those days are the lightest in his football workload. 
</P>
<P>
	``He doesn't want any sympathy,'' Broughton said. ``He just  
wants us to focus on camp and getting better. He just keeps saying 
he can handle it. I didn't even know he was getting chemo 
treatments until somebody else told me. That's how strong he is.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Breaux is still awaiting back surgery. As for the chemotherapy  
and its effects, he shrugs. 
</P>
<P>
	``I get a little bit nauseous from time to time, but that's it.  
And I can handle that,'' he said. ``Hey, when you're a football 
coach, this is what you enjoy doing, and that's why I'm out here.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990801.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 13:40:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Don't Call U.S. Swimmers a 'B' Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WINNIPEG, Manitoba (AP) -- You can call the United States  
swimming team at the Pan American Games anything you want. Just 
don't call it a `B' team. 
</P>
<P>
	``I definitely dismiss that as hogwash,'' women's coach Pete  
Malone said. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of people classify us as a `B' team, but I think we'll  
have just as good times as our `A' team,'' Beth Botsford, a 1996 
Olympic gold medalist in the women's 100-meter backstroke and 400 
medley relay, said. ``That's why I don't consider this a `B' 
team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Technically, the Americans were split into three teams this  
year: the `A' team will compete in the Pan Pacific Games later this 
month in Sydney; the `B' team was designated for the Pan Am Games; 
and the `C' team competed recently in the World University Games at 
Palma de Mallorca, Spain. 
</P>
<P>
	``A lot of people on this team could be on the Pan Pacific  
team,'' Scott Tucker, a member of the men's Olympic gold 
medal-winning 400 freestyle relay team, said. ``A lot of people 
have improved since last summer when the teams were selected. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't consider this a `B' team at all.''  
</P>
<P>
	Neither does men's coach Gregg Troy.  
</P>
<P>
	``We've been termed a normally weaker team than we send to the  
Pan Am Games,'' he said. ``But this team is like the one we sent 
four years ago and that team did exceptionally well. It rose above 
its expectations. 
</P>
<P>
	``This team is not seeded well, but there's no need to take us  
lightly. We might be a little vulnerable, but I think the athletes 
will respond well to the challenge.'' 
</P>
<P>
	They certainly responded well in 1995 at Mar del Plata,  
Argentina, winning 23 individual medals, including eight golds, in 
13 men's events, plus all three relays. They also took 22 
individual medals, nine golds, in 13 women's events and won the 
three relays. 
</P>
<P>
	This time, the best men's hopes are Tucker in the 100 and 200  
freestyle, and in the 400 and 800 freestyle relays; Aaron Piersol, 
16, the youngest American ever to break two minutes in the 200 
backstroke; Sabir Muhammad, the team's biggest member at 6-foot-7 
and the American record holder in the 100 freestyle; and Mark 
Gangloff, 16, the team's youngest member, in the 200 breaststroke. 
</P>
<P>
	The top women's swimmers include Botsford, in the 100 and 200  
backstroke; Kaitlin Sandeno, the national champion in the 400 
individual medley, who will compete in the 400 and 800 freestyle; 
and Katie Yevak, the national champion in the 200 breaststroke. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't have a lot of athletes who have been tested  
internationally,'' Troy said. ``The Brazilians will be very good 
and the Canadians will be focused, because they are at home and 
it's a big chance for them to be successful. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's a good chance we could dominate the total medals, but  
not dominate the gold medals.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Two of the golds are expected to go to Brazil's Gustavo Borges,  
the defending champion in the 100 and 200 freestyle. Another 
favorite from Brazil is Fernando Scherer, the 1996 Olympic bronze 
medalist in the 50 freestyle and the fifth-fastest swimmer ever. 
</P>
<P>
	The top Canadian is Curtis Myden, the Olympic bronze medalist in  
the 400 individual medley and the ninth-fastest ever. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're looking for people to stand up here,'' Troy said. ``This  
is a chance for our young swimmers to establish themselves for next 
year's Olympic trials.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Tucker also sees this as an opportunity for the U.S. team to  
assert its vaunted power. 
</P>
<P>
	``Calling this a `B' team is more motivation for us,'' he said.  
``All we have to do is go out and prove how good we are. 
</P>
<P>
	``We haven't brought the `B' thing up as an issue. We don't  
think anything about it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Neither do the women.  
</P>
<P>
	``Since October we've only talked them about where we want to be  
in Sydney next year,'' Malone said. ``A lot of swimmers on this 
team are ahead of those on the `A' team. This is a long journey for 
them and it won't end until after the Olympic Games in Australia.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The six-day swimming competition begins Monday with finals in  
the women's 100 freestyle, 400 individual medley and 800 freestyle 
relay, and the men's 100 breaststroke and 200 freestyle. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990801.0074 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 12:30:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Bradley: Taiwan Should Temper Talk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The United States must make clear that Taiwan  
should not expect U.S. aid if Taiwan's unilateral moves toward 
independence provoke a Chinese invasion, Democratic presidential 
candidate Bill Bradley said Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley, speaking on NBC's ``Meet the Press,'' said the United  
States is committed to helping Taiwan against a Chinese military 
strike. But the United States ``should say to the Taiwanese 
government that if they take steps toward independence, they cannot 
count on us for any help.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley, who is challenging Vice President Al Gore for the  
Democratic nomination next year, said ``we would be there'' if 
China takes military action against Taiwan in the absence of a move 
toward independence. 
</P>
<P>
	Taiwan's president, Lee Teng-Hui, recently angered Beijing by  
suggesting he no longer supported the one-China policy under which 
Taiwan and China, separated after a 1949 civil war, ostensibly are 
committed to eventual reunification. 
</P>
<P>
	On the campaign front, Bradley said he was ``actually shocked  
that the Gore campaign attacked me so strongly'' after Bradley 
urged Democratic and Republican candidates for president to decline 
``soft money'' contributions -- the largely unregulated donations to 
political parties. 
</P>
<P>
	The Gore camp, in a letter, accused the former New Jersey  
senator of dropping the fight for campaign finance reform when he 
quit the Senate ``for private life and $2 million in special 
interest speaking and consulting fees.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bradley said it was ironic that a Republican presidential  
hopeful, Sen. John McCain of Arizona, was the only one to agree 
that candidates should refuse to accept soft money. McCain has been 
a leader in efforts to change campaign finance law. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990801.0075 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 12:30:36 </DATE_TIME>
