<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 17:00:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cuba Baseball Wins Olympic Berth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WINNIPEG, Manitoba (AP) -- Cuba won a return trip to the  
Olympics, beating a stubborn Canadian team and overcoming the 
distraction of a ninth-inning protester for a 3-2 victory Sunday in 
the Pan Am baseball semifinals. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cubans, Olympic champions in 1992 and 1996, will meet the  
United States or Mexico for the Pan Am gold medal Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	It was sweet revenge for the Cubans, who were rocked by  
preliminary-round losses to Canada, 8-1, and the United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Omar Linares, regarded as his nation's best player, hit a  
two-out, three-run homer in the third inning. Jose Ibar pitched 5 
1-3 innings of strong relief before he lost concentration after 
retiring the first batter in the ninth. 
</P>
<P>
	That's when a man carrying a ``Human Right First'' sign came  
onto the field in front of the mound. Cuba's Yobal Duenas rushed 
out of the dugout with his country's flag and tried to wrap up the 
protester. 
</P>
<P>
	The man, wearing a shirt with ``Freedom'' written on the front,  
then ran behind the plate. Cuban catcher Ariel Pestano tried to 
stop the protester with his mask before the man ran in front of the 
Canadian dugout, where he was apparently hit by Cuban second 
baseman Juan Padilla and knocked down. Authorities then took the 
man away. 
</P>
<P>
	Ibar, apparently shaken, then gave up a single to Todd Betts,  
threw a wild pitch and walked Ryan Radmanovich before Luis Lazo 
came on to strike out the final two hitters. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this year when the Cubans beat the Baltimore Orioles in  
an exhibition at Camden Yards, a protester ran onto the field 
before he was tackled by a Cuban umpire. 
</P>
<P>
	Canadian left fielder Aaron Guiel, who would later strike out to  
end the game -- manager Ernie Whitt moments earlier protested he was 
hit with a pitch that was ruled a foul ball -- was in front of the 
dugout when the protester was trying to get away. 
</P>
<P>
	``The guy made us all look bad,'' Guiel said. ``But what is  
great about the U.S. and Canada is that you have the freedom to do 
that. I don't agree with what he did and I also don't agree with 
Cuba's politics, either.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When Canada beat Cuba 8-1 in the opening round, Guiel twice ran  
over Pestano at the plate. And then Sunday, he was nearly in the 
middle of another physical confrontation as the protester fled the 
angry Cubans. 
</P>
<P>
	``One of their coaches tried to throw a punch and another player  
tried to throw his mask at him. I had my bat in my hand and another 
guy was beside me,'' Guiel said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We just stood in between. It's a good thing for them they  
didn't show any aggression toward us. Then there would have been 
some real trouble.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``In a way I understand it. But basically those guys are  
brainwashed into thinking the way their country runs is the way it 
should be run. ...Unfortunately it was a little blemish on the 
game, a great game.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The loss was a tough one for Canada, which had won all five of  
its games entering the semifinals. 
</P>
<P>
	``Probably the toughest loss I've ever had to take,'' Guiel  
said. ``We were one run, one blooper, one error away from 
qualifying for the Olympics.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Canadians took a 2-0 lead against starter Norge Vera on a  
wild pitch with runners at first and third in the second and a 
third-inning solo homer from Stubby Clapp. 
</P>
<P>
	Canadian starter Mike Meyers retired the first two batters in  
the third before Luis Ulacia and Isacc Martinez singled. Linares 
then drove a long homer to left. 
</P>
<P>
	Ibar relieved in the fourth and allowed only one hit into the  
ninth. 
</P>
<P>
	After Lazo got the final two outs, the Cubans swarmed their  
hefty relief pitcher and several players once again came running 
out of the dugout with their flag, taking a short celebratory jaunt 
up the left field line. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cubans did not comment after the game, but their actions  
made it clear how relieved they were to qualify for the gold medal 
game -- and for the Olympics. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
