<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 12:40:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Drug Test Takes Away Canada Medal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WINNIPEG, Manitoba (AP) -- Canada was stripped of its gold medal  
in roller hockey at the Pan Am Games Sunday, because its goaltender 
tested positive for banned substances. The gold now goes to the 
United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Canadian goaltender Steve Vezina of Montreal tested positive for  
two stimulants and an anabolic steroid, games officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Argentina now gets the silver medal, while Brazil the bronze.  
This was the first time roller hockey was held in the Pan Am Games. 
</P>
<P>
	The positive test was the first drug scandal at the Winnipeg  
Games. 
</P>
<P>
	Mario Vazquez Rana, president of the Pan American Sports  
Organization, said the level of the substances found in Vezina's 
urine left no doubt that he had broken the rules. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a clear case of violation,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Canada beat the United States 7-6 Tuesday for the gold medal.  
</P>
<P>
	Roller hockey is one of six sports on the Pan Am program that is  
not an Olympic sport. 
</P>
<P>
	Vezina tested positive for ephedrine, a stimulant often used for  
hay fever, pseudoephrine and an anabolic steroid, Nandrolene. 
</P>
<P>
	Games officials dismissed the possibility that Vezina had taken  
the stimulants for medical purposes, saying that the concentrations 
were too high in his urine to indicate such usage. No amount of 
anabolic steroid is permitted. 
</P>
<P>
	The stimulants would allow an athlete to avoid fatigue, while  
the steroid would allow the buildup of muscle mass. 
</P>
<P>
	Vezina -- a distant relative of Canadian hockey great Georges  
Vezina -- for whom the NHL's annual award for the best goaltender is 
named. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990801.0078 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 17:10:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Falcons' Chandler Still Throws Deep </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREENVILLE, S.C. (AP) -- The anxiousness shows in his face.  
Clearly, Chris Chandler is a bit worried in the early days of 
training camp. 
</P>
<P>
	After answering his critics by taking the Atlanta Falcons to  
their first Super Bowl -- his, too, for that matter -- Chandler 
wonders if there's anyone to take advantage of his robust right 
arm. 
</P>
<P>
	``That is definitely an area of concern,'' the Falcons  
quarterback said. ``I like throwing deep balls. I like doing it a 
lot better when a guy has the ability to get deep.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Chandler had his greatest season in 1998, throwing for 3,154  
yards and 25 touchdowns, but he faces a major obstacle if he's to 
duplicate those numbers. Tony Martin, the team's fastest receiver 
who caught 66 passes for 1,181 yards a year ago, was released in 
the offseason after being indicted on money laundering charges. 
</P>
<P>
	Now playing with his hometown Miami Dolphins, Martin goes on  
trial Monday morning in a south Florida courtroom. Chandler, 
meanwhile, returns to the practice field at Furman University, 
wondering what the verdict will be on the Falcons future. 
</P>
<P>
	``Tony had the knack of being able to get open deep,'' Chandler  
said. ``I have to deal with it like we're going to get it worked 
out. We still have 5 1/2 weeks until that first game. That what's 
we're grinding away at.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Terance Mathis had similar numbers to Martin -- 64 receptions,  
1,136 yards -- but he lacks the size and speed of his former running 
mate. The Falcons signed Chris Calloway, the Giants' leading 
receiver, but he's more of a possession-type receiver. 
</P>
<P>
	Tim Dwight has Martin-type speed but much work to do on running  
precise routes. Ditto for Ronnie Harris. Besides, those two have a 
grand total of 12 career receptions. 
</P>
<P>
	``With Tony on the field, we didn't see as much early-down  
blitzing,'' Chandler said. ``His ability to beat people deep was a 
threat that teams had to deal with. I think they defensed us 
differently because of that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	To make matters worse, 1,846-yard rusher Jamal Anderson is  
refusing to report to training camp unless he gets a new contract. 
For now, Chandler looks like a man alone, forced to carry an 
inordinate burden in the Falcons' offense. 
</P>
<P>
	``He certainly has the ability to do that,'' coach Dan Reeves  
said. ``I don't think the pressure would bother him if we have to 
rely more on the passing game to open up the running game. He knows 
the system we've got and he's comfortable with the system we've 
got.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Six months later, Chandler doesn't look back on the greatest  
season of his career. For now, his most vivid reminder is the 34-19 
loss to John Elway and the Denver Broncos in the Super Bowl. 
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe some day, if we don't get back there again and that's  
all the Super Bowl experience I get, I'll probably look back and 
maybe think it was pretty neat,'' he said. ``But right now, when 
we're in the middle of training camp and trying to get back there, 
there's no time for reflecting.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990801.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 12:36:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Volker Sets World Backstroke Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ISTANBUL, Turkey (AP) -- Germany's Sandra Volker broke her world  
record in the 50-meter backstroke at the European Swimming 
Championships on Sunday, and Pieter Van den Hoogenband of the 
Netherlands emerged as the new star of the meet. 
</P>
<P>
	Volker was first off the blocks to finish in 28.71 seconds and  
defeat Spain's Nina Jivanevskaia (29.02). Metka Sparavec of 
Slovenia got the bronze in 29.25. Volker broke her mark of 28.78 
last month in Monte Carlo. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't know myself where I got the power from for this world  
record,'' Volker said. ``All the races seem to have drained me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Holland's Pieter Van den Hoogenband defeated world and European  
champion Alexander Popov of Russia, swimming the 50-meter freestyle 
in 22.06. The Russian left the pool with his first bronze medal, 
behind Italy's Lorenzo Vismara. Vismara was second in 22.21 while 
Popov clocked 22.32. 
</P>
<P>
	Hoogenband has been unbeatable so far, delivering fast  
performances in every one of the five events he has entered. 
Holland's disqualification in the 800 relay Saturday robbed him of 
the fastest relay leg of all time in 1:45.20. 
</P>
<P>
	Runaway record breaker Inge de Bruijn took her 50-meter  
freestyle race in 24.99. Therese Alshammar of Sweden was second in 
25.30 and Alison Sheppard of Britain was third in 25.33. 
</P>
<P>
	Marcel Wouda, another star in the new Dutch swimming powerhouse,  
goes for gold in the 400 medley. But he faces tough competition 
from Italy's Alessio Boggiatto, Spain's Frederik Hviid, and 
Germany's Jirka Letzin. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dutch pair of Kirsten Vlieghuis and Cara Geurts are favored  
in the 400-meter women's freestyle, with their main competition 
coming from Camelia Potec of Romania. 
</P>
<P>
	In the 200-meter women's butterfly, Denmark goes for its first  
medal with Mette Jacobsen, who swims against Katrin Jaeke of 
Germany and Spain's Maria Pelaez. 
</P>
<P>
	The 11-day meet ends with the men and women's 400 medley relays.  
There also will be finals in women's 10-meter synchronized diving 
and the men's 3-meter springboard. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
