<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Stocks Fall in Early Trading / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The dollar declined against the yen early Monday,  
following through from last week's weakness. Japanese stocks fell 
following another decline on Wall Street. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 114.84 yen in early trading, down 0.42 yen  
from late Friday in Tokyo but unchanged from its late New York 
level Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average shed 110.86 points,  
or 0.62 percent, to 17,751.00 in the first 30 minutes of trading. 
On Friday, the average closed down 8.06 points, or 0.05 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, traders said the dollar's basic weakness  
remained unchanged. The greenback last traded in the 114-yen range 
in Tokyo on Feb. 15. 
</P>
<P>
	In New York on Friday, the dollar dropped to a five-month low of  
114.20 yen on worries over the general state of the U.S. economy. 
The Dow Jones industrial average slid for a second straight session 
Friday, losing 136.14 points, or 1.3 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The greenback has been weak against major currencies in recent  
weeks, including the yen and the euro, on fears of inflation in the 
United States and expectations of an economic recovery in Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	Inflation fears have risen since the U.S. Labor Department said  
its Employment Cost Index rose 1.1 percent in the second quarter of 
this year, a larger-than-expected jump. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 122.42 yen, down  
from 123.46 yen late Friday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, share prices opened lower amid concerns  
about the strong yen as well as the weakness on Wall Street last 
week. 
</P>
<P>
	A weaker dollar cuts into the overseas profits of Japanese  
companies when translated into yen. Despite some signs of an 
economic recovery, many Japanese companies are struggling to bail 
out of the country's worst economic slowdown in 50 years. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was down 13.52 points, or 0.91 percent, to 1,465.41. 
The TOPIX closed down 11.20 points, or 0.76 percent, on Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark No. 214 10-year Japanese government  
bond rose to 1.820 percent from Friday's finish of 1.7850 percent, 
driving its price down to 99.82 yen from 100.12 yen. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
