<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dolphins' Collins Rushes to Forefront </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT LAUDERDALE (AP) -- In a spirited intrasquad scrimmage that  
featured a melee, Dolphins rookie running back Cecil Collins 
vaulted to the forefront of Miami's overcrowded backfield. 
</P>
<P>
	Collins, the Dolphins fifth-round pick whose draft value dropped  
because of several off-field trangressions, rushed for 63 yards on 
13 carries, including a 40-yard touchdown on an off-tackle burst. 
</P>
<P>
	``Unfortunately, someone's got to start, but we're all competing  
for jobs,'' said Collins, who played in just six collegiate games 
at Louisiana State and McNeese State. ``But when it comes down to 
it, we're all teammates.'' 
</P>
<P>
	It didn't look that way early on in the controlled scrimmage at  
Lockhart Stadium -- the home of the MLS Fusion -- when defensive back 
Terrell Buckley took offense to a downfield block thrown by tight 
end Hunter Goodwin. The two came to blows and ignited a team melee. 
</P>
<P>
	Red-faced Dolphins coach Jimmy Johnson ran on the field to break  
it up and then read his troops the riot act during a team meeting 
in front of 15,684 fans. 
</P>
<P>
	``I could tolerate a little altercation during practice, but not  
like it,'' Johnson said. ``and not during a game or scrimmage when 
it will cost you 15 yards. I will not have it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Collins' performance was clearly the high point for the  
large crowd. 
</P>
<P>
	Collins, kicked out of both universities after being arrested  
for unlawful entry, battery and failing drug tests, was serenaded 
by fans with chants of ``Dies-el, Dies-el.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I hope everyone is for me,'' said Collins, 23. ``I'm just  
trying to help the team as much as I can and give 110 percent.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While Collins isn't expected to displace incumbent starter Karim  
Abdul-Jabbar right away, he is fighting for a role in a backfield 
logjam that includes second-round pick J.J. Johnson, Giants castoff 
Tyrone Wheatley, speedy John Avery and versatile rookie fullback 
Rob Konrad. 
</P>
<P>
	Avery, expected to be the third-down back, had five catches for  
54 yards in the scrimmage. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson rushed for 15 yards on nine carries, while Abdul-Jabbar  
ripped off an impressive 31-yard run in a brief appearance. Juan 
Johnson, a free-agent running back out of Utah, gained 31 yards on 
five carries. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheatley did little to attract attention, amassing 18 yards on  
seven attempts. 
</P>
<P>
	Konrad, a 6-foot-3, 255-pounder, stood out, gaining 10 yards on  
two carries and catching four passes for 52 yards. 
</P>
<P>
	``Konrad's been solid all camp and will be a good player for  
us,'' Jimmy Johnson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Dan Marino directed the first two of eight 12-play series,  
completing five of eight passes for 37 yards, including an 11-yard 
touchdown strike to Yatil Green. Green, the Dolphins' first-round 
pick in 1997 who has yet to play a down in a regular season NFL 
game after sustaining two major knee injuries, had two catches for 
17 yards. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
