<DOCNO> APW19990801.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 12:29:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Patch Could Alter Aneurysm Surgery </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- George Huffman had a time bomb in his abdomen:  
A weak bulging spot on the largest blood vessel in his body that, 
if it broke, would cause almost instantly fatal internal bleeding. 
</P>
<P>
	Surgery to patch that artery, the aorta, is among the most  
grueling operations known -- the entire abdomen is sliced open and 
delicate organs moved aside just to reach the problem spot. Surgery 
kills up to 10 percent of patients, and even those who do well can 
require months of recuperation. 
</P>
<P>
	Hoping to avoid traumatic surgery, Huffman volunteered to have  
an experimental patch, as thick as his index finger, threaded up 
his body through an artery in his leg. It worked. The Hickory, 
N.C., lawyer spent just one night in the hospital, and a week later 
was back at work. 
</P>
<P>
	Thousands of Americans with abdominal aortic aneurysms soon may  
get to opt for Huffman's easier therapy. 
</P>
<P>
	The first minimally invasive treatments, competing surgical  
devices made by Guidant Corp. and Medtronic Inc., are awaiting 
final Food and Drug Administration review after government advisers 
last month recommended their approval. 
</P>
<P>
	They will not be for everyone -- indeed, FDA's advisers worried  
the new devices may be dangerous for certain women -- and surgeons 
need careful training in the extremely difficult procedure. 
</P>
<P>
	But some surgeons say the devices could revolutionize care,  
particularly for elderly patients who could not survive regular 
surgery and today have no options. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's really a quantum leap in terms of therapy,'' said Dr.  
David Deaton of East Carolina University, who helped test Guidant's 
device. ``This technique is in its infancy and it's already clearly 
better, for the right patient.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Doctors estimate that 1.5 million older Americans have abdominal  
aortic aneurysms, called ``AAAs.'' But because AAAs often cause no 
symptoms until the lifethreatening day they break, only about 
200,000 patients are aware of the problem. 
</P>
<P>
	The aorta is the largest blood vessel, like a river running from  
the heart to the groin with tributaries that branch off carrying 
blood around the body. 
</P>
<P>
	An aneurysm is a weak bulge in the aorta's wall. As blood pounds  
past, the pressure can cause that balloon-like spot to burst -- 
killing 15,000 Americans a year. 
</P>
<P>
	Aneurysms big enough to risk bursting require surgery to patch  
them. 
</P>
<P>
	The experimental alternative to that grueling operation: slice  
an opening into an artery in the groin; thread the aortic patch up 
that artery until it meets the aorta; then push the patch to the 
aneurysm spot. 
</P>
<P>
	The patch must extend like a sleeve inside the aorta, providing  
a new path so blood does not continue to pressure the weakened 
aorta wall. 
</P>
<P>
	Guidant's patch, Ancure, has little metal hooks that grab onto a  
healthy section of aorta to form that sleeve. 
</P>
<P>
	Medtronic's AneuRx is a stent, a metal scaffolding that opens up  
until it has expanded against the aortic walls enough to hold the 
patch in place. 
</P>
<P>
	In clinical trials of about 800 patients, the companies found  
the devices successfully repaired over 90 percent of AAAs, cut in 
half surgical side effects and sent patients home from the hospital 
in two to three days instead of six to nine. 
</P>
<P>
	But it was not risk-free. Even though fewer women than men get  
AAAs, FDA's advisers said women actually fared worse with the 
experimental procedure. 
</P>
<P>
	The problem is size, Deaton said: Often doctors did not realize  
in advance that many women's arteries were too small for the 
procedure. Efforts are being made to better choose women patients, 
and women whose arteries are big enough do fine, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Also troubling was that some patches leaked. It is unclear how  
risky that is -- how often that leak would build up enough to 
rupture, said FDA cardiologist Dr. John Stuhlmuller. 
</P>
<P>
	Leaks can be retreated, something required for 4.5 percent of  
patients, said Dr. Christopher Zarins of Stanford University, who 
tested Medtronic's device.	   But, ``with surgery, there's a very clear, upfront risk'' of 
complications or death in the operating room, Stuhlmuller said. 
``With the devices, the upfront morbidity and mortality is clearly 
lower. What's uncertain is the long-term risk.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Regardless of that uncertainty, ``patients love it,'' Zarins  
said of the new procedure. ``They're elderly, they don't want to 
have a big operation.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The FDA's advisers concluded the key is choosing the right  
patient -- someone whose risks from open surgery outweighs that 
long-term uncertainty. 
</P>
<P>
	Also key is surgeon training.  
</P>
<P>
	``This is clearly the hardest endovascular procedure I've ever  
been exposed to,'' Deaton said, comparing it to building a model 
ship inside a bottle. But ``if you pick the right patient, things 
go quite well.'' 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990801.0087 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 16:20:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chiefs' QB Grbac Must Prove Himself </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- Nobody understands better than Elvis  
Grbac what a critical year this is for Elvis Grbac. 
</P>
<P>
	No longer a kid, the Kansas City Chiefs quarterback is closing  
in on the sunny side of 30. In his seventh year in the NFL, the 
talented young guy with all the bright promise stands on the brink 
of becoming a discarded, unfulfilled veteran. 
</P>
<P>
	Failing for a third straight year to stay healthy and productive  
for an entire season could prove ruinous to any future he might 
envision with the Chiefs, who would probably look elsewhere for the 
starting quarterback they thought they were getting from San 
Francisco in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'll be 29 in two weeks,'' Grbac said. ``I think I'm at the  
point where I feel comfortable in this system. I feel comfortable 
with this organization and the players I have around me. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's time to just go out and start winning games on a  
consistent basis. I think this is the year I should do that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Since coming to Kansas City, injuries have been the biggest  
problem for the 6-foot-5 Cleveland native. A fractured left 
clavicle cost him six games in 1997, but still he was 8-2 in 10 
starts for a 13-3 team and the Chiefs were encouraged. 
</P>
<P>
	But last season was a total disaster. He was benched because of  
injury and poor play and caught most of the blame for a miserable 
7-9 campaign that kept Kansas City out of the playoffs for the 
second time in three years. 
</P>
<P>
	Late in the season, as his confidence vanished and popular  
backup Rich Gannon proved more productive, Grbac was even booed by 
the Arrowhead Stadium crowd. 
</P>
<P>
	Damaging his standing even more, he publicly criticized his  
teammates and drew fire from all sides following a 20-13 loss to 
Pittsburgh in a Monday night debacle. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, with Gannon gone to Oakland as a free agent and 42-year-old  
Warren Moon providing backup, Grbac goes into this season carrying 
the tattered image of a chronic underachiever and injury-prone 
loser. 
</P>
<P>
	And the pressure to perform is greater than ever.  
</P>
<P>
	``Yeah, I'd like to improve my image and do the things that  
every quarterback does. But the most important thing is winning 
games,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Last year was such a disappointment. I've just got to stay  
healthy and compete and get this team ready for the season. My 
image will be changed by the way we play, and the way we win games. 
We have to win at all costs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Chiefs cannot be blamed for hanging with Grbac. At times,  
both in San Francisco and Kansas City, he has flashed great 
promise. He has a strong arm and runs remarkably well for a man his 
size. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am as committed to Elvis as I am to any player on this  
team,'' said first-year coach Gunther Cunningham, who was promoted 
from defensive coordinator after Marty Schottenheimer resigned. 
</P>
<P>
	But everyone knows there's a limit to the organization's  
patience. 
</P>
<P>
	``The last two years have been disappointing for myself and,  
last year, for the entire team,' Grbac said. ``Every year you go 
through the league you're going to learn something. It's been a 
good learning process for me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``But I'm getting tired of it. I just want to start winning  
games.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
