<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> US 92, Dominican Republic 80 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WINNIPEG, Manitoba (AP) -- Nothing like a little morning run to  
work out the frustrations from the night before. 
</P>
<P>
	Hours after suffering its worst loss ever in women's basketball  
at the Pan American Games, the United States awoke early Sunday and 
beat the Dominican Republic 92-80 to clinch a berth in the medal 
round. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think any basketball team when you lose by 30 points the  
game before, you want to come out and reprove yourself that you're 
not that bad,'' U.S. guard Michelle Marciniak said. 
</P>
<P>
	``The only thing we wanted to do was push the ball up and down  
the floor and get into the flow of a basketball game and just 
play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. men also played, meeting Brazil later Sunday.  
</P>
<P>
	The women (2-1), who lost to Cuba 95-64 on Saturday night, got  
their running game going for the first time in the tournament, 
resulting in a succession of layups and easy baskets inside. 
</P>
<P>
	Only two U.S. baskets came from outside 10 feet -- a pair of  
3-pointers by Marciniak, who scored 16 points. Lynn Pride, driving 
the baseline at will, led the Americans with 20 points and 11 
rebounds, Danielle McCulley scored 11 and Edwina Brown 10. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm excited to see us score that much,'' U.S. coach Nell  
Fortner said. ``Our transition game was working today and we took 
it at them. And that was one of our goals. Don't settle for 
pull-ups, take it to the hole. We didn't think they could guard 
us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The only problem for the Americans was that for much of the  
game, they couldn't guard Teresa Duran, who led all scorers with 33 
points. 
</P>
<P>
	Duran's 3-pointer drew the Dominican Republic (0-3) to 75-68  
with 9:52 remaining. But she made only two more baskets and the her 
team never got that close again as the taller Americans continued 
to pound away inside. 
</P>
<P>
	Pride, the most athletic of the U.S. players, was only 6-for-18  
in the first two games. She made a number of nice moves, but 
couldn't get the shots to fall. Sunday, she finished those moves, 
making six of her first eight shots and finishing 8-for-16. 
</P>
<P>
	``We tried to work with Lynn on making the easy play,'' Fortner  
said. ``Sometimes she makes the shot harder than it actually is. Go 
up and make the easy shot, just turn and shoot the ball. She really 
concentrated on that today.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Pride, who'll be a senior at Kansas, said it was all in her  
head. 
</P>
<P>
	``I just had a whole different attitude this game,'' she said.  
``It was a big game and I knew I had to come out mentally prepared. 
It was just go up, because they really couldn't match up with us in 
the post area.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brazil (3-0), Canada (2-1) and Cuba (2-1) also made the  
semifinals. The final two days of preliminary play will determine 
the seedings. 
</P>
<P>
	The Americans play Brazil on Monday and Canada on Wednesday.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
