<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fla. Plans No Agent-Player Changes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WINTER HAVEN, Fla. (AP) -- Florida coach Steve Spurrier plans no  
changes in the way his program monitors player activity with 
agents, despite a troubled stretch during which five of his former 
players were accused of making improper contact. 
</P>
<P>
	``It will have no effect at all,'' Spurrier said Sunday,  
speaking during the media's annual gathering with the state's 
college coaches. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm very disappointed these players made a bad choice,'' he  
said. ``It's a bad choice they've got to live with now. It's 
unfortunate to them. But it's no reflection on the school.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Thus far, the NCAA and Southeastern Conference seem to agree.  
Neither appears ready to sanction Florida after three players -- 
Jevon Kearse, Johnny Rutledge and Reggie McGrew -- gave sworn 
affidavits admitting to taking improper payments from sports agent 
Tank Black's company. 
</P>
<P>
	Another two players, Tim Beauchamp and Dock Pollard, were  
accused of improper contact with a runner for another agent and 
were dismissed before the Orange Bowl. 
</P>
<P>
	None of the players are still at Florida.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's unfortunate,'' Spurrier said. ``Because those guys did a  
good job as players, but they made bad choices as people. It was a 
very bad choice they didn't have to make.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Spurrier, athletic director Jeremy Foley and other officials at  
Florida have harped on the fact that they consistently remind 
players that taking money from agents is not allowed. 
</P>
<P>
	Florida State coach Bobby Bowden, who had an agent problem  
earlier in the decade, said his school takes similar measures but 
insists the problem comes down to one, simple issue. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's pure honesty,'' Bowden said. ``If the agents were honest,  
we'd have no problems. It comes down to honesty from the agents and 
from the players. It's the ones that won't abide by the rules that 
are killing us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bowden said it's easy to figure out why problems persist at  
schools like Florida and Florida State. 
</P>
<P>
	``You notice how some schools don't have as many problems with  
agents, because they've got no players,'' he said. ``So, they make 
a living in Florida. It's obvious that you'll see more of them here 
than at a school that doesn't have a pro prospect.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Spurrier doesn't feel there are any additional precautions that  
can be taken, either at Florida or on a national level, to prevent 
runners from infiltrating campuses and luring some players into 
taking money. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a free country,'' he said. ``Players know the rules and  
they can abide by them, or they can break them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If they do so at Florida, they face being excommunicated from  
their school. It's an action Spurrier hopes has a profound effect 
on Kearse, Rutledge and McGrew, three of the most talented 
defenders in school history. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this summer, the coach said none of those players are  
allowed to associate with Gator football anymore. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
