<HEADLINE> Diana Fund Helps Violence Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- Trustees of the Princess Diana memorial fund  
announced Monday that grants totaling $4.8 million would help 
victims of violence, including women raped in Rwanda, 
war-traumatized Bosnians, and refugees from Sierra Leone. 
</P>
<P>
	About $1.6 million of the new grants will go to groups clearing  
landmines in Afghanistan, Cambodia and Angola, or working for a 
global ban of the devices, a cause in which Diana took a special 
interest. 
</P>
<P>
	``This first round of international grants under our long-term  
policies reflects our determination to reach out to some of the 
most vulnerable people in the world, bringing hope to lives broken 
by violence,'' fund Chief Executive Andrew Purkis said in a 
statement. 
</P>
<P>
	The Diana, Princess of Wales, Memorial Fund has built up $115.2  
million in investments and plans to distribute at least $6.4 
million a year to causes the princess supported, its executors say. 
</P>
<P>
	The fund was set up immediately after Diana, ex-wife of heir to  
the British throne Prince Charles, was killed in a Paris car crash 
in August 1997. She was 36. 
</P>
<P>
	The fund receives donations and profits from the sale of  
approved mementos. 
</P>
<P>
	The beneficiaries announced Sunday included:  
</P>
<P>
	--Children in the Andes, $120,000.  
</P>
<P>
	--Acord, $272,000, to support Rwandan women who survived the  
genocide. 
</P>
<P>
	--Children's Legal Centre, $140,300, for children in war-affected  
areas of Kosovo, Liberia and Sri Lanka. 
</P>
<P>
	--Christian Aid, $143,400, for war victims in Sierra Leone.  
</P>
<P>
	--Rwanda Survivors Fund, $41,000, to help young rape victims.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
