<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> China Ups Punishment for Price Fix </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- After 21 months of deflation, China has issued  
new rules with tougher punishments for businesses that fail to 
follow government pricing policies, state media reported Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	The regulations, drafted by the government's State Development  
Planning Commission, specify fines and punishment for various price 
violations. They also list punitive measures for the charging of 
unauthorized fees, according to the official Xinhua News Agency. 
</P>
<P>
	The rules ``will play a positive role in preventing price  
irregularities, maintaining a good market order for fair and open 
competition,'' Xinhua reported. 
</P>
<P>
	Faced with overcapacity and market gluts, China's manufacturers  
have recently slashed prices or, in some cases, forged alliances 
with competitors to keep prices aloft. 
</P>
<P>
	China's existing price law made low-price dumping, price fraud  
and price monopolies illegal. 
</P>
<P>
	Nonetheless, many of China's industries -- from televisions to  
computers and through a range of home appliances -- are fighting 
price wars. Sinking steel prices forced the government to impose 
price limits. 
</P>
<P>
	Weak consumer demand has sent China's benchmark for inflation,  
the retail price index, lower for 21 months in a row. For the first 
half of 1999, retail prices slid 3.2 percent, dropping 3.4 percent 
in June alone. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990801.0101 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 09:30:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bush's Business Contacts Pay Off </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) -- Familiarity has bred profits for George  
W. Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	The Republican presidential candidate has spent much of his  
career relying on family friends and making longtime buddies out of 
his business contacts. 
</P>
<P>
	From all indications, he has done it profitably for himself and  
kept the friendships to boot. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's hard to go anywhere without running into a friend of  
his,'' said Karen Hughes, who has worked for Bush as a spokeswoman 
for five years. 
</P>
<P>
	A one-time clothing salesman and ranchhand, Bush has taken a  
career path through the oil patch, onto baseball's field of dreams 
and into the political briar patch as Texas governor. 
</P>
<P>
	Much of his business success has come from brokering deals with  
folks he knew. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush received a master's degree in business administration from  
Harvard Business School, a move he called ``a vocational training 
exercise in capitalism.'' 
</P>
<P>
	After graduation in 1975 he headed west through the far plains  
of Texas and decided to stop at the Midland oil fields. Crude 
prices were skyrocketing and he said he was attracted by the 
``entrepreneurial fever'' following the Arab oil embargo. 
</P>
<P>
	He started as a landman, checking deeds and mineral rights, and  
two years later founded an exploration firm putting together 
private partnerships for drilling ventures. He named it Arbusto, 
meaning bush in Spanish. The company did not begin active 
operations until 1979 -- a year after Bush made an unsuccessful bid 
for a congressional seat. 
</P>
<P>
	The first oil well he drilled was dry and Bush said he would  
never forget the feeling that the whole business would not be quite 
as easy as he had thought it would be. 
</P>
<P>
	His company actually drilled few wells. Instead, Bush primarily  
brokered deals or participated in those put together by others. 
</P>
<P>
	Russell S. Reynolds Jr., now a director at Oppenheimer Fund,  
Inc., was an individual investor in Arbusto. A longtime family 
friend, Reynolds got back only about 20 cents on the dollar for his 
investment in the business. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, he does not blame Bush, saying he thought that the whole  
thing was handled well, except ``you always like to make money 
instead of losing it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Reynolds recently attended a campaign dinner in Connecticut for  
Bush and is still undecided whether he will have a formal role in 
this election. 
</P>
<P>
	By 1982, Arbusto was on hard times. The company had less than  
$50,000 in the bank. The company also was about $420,000 in debt. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush changed the name of the company to Bush Exploration Co. and  
took the business public. 
</P>
<P>
	During the same time period, Bush was named a director of United  
Bank of Midland. While he was a director, the bank loaned his 
company $372,000. The deal was later scrutinized, although a 
committee of the bank, which did not include Bush, had approved the 
loan. The money was repaid. 
</P>
<P>
	It was not long afterward that Bush's company merged with  
Spectrum 7 Energy Corp., a firm of Cincinnati-based investors who 
backed independent oil producers. 
</P>
<P>
	Spectrum itself was struggling. Languishing in a depressed oil  
market, within two years the company merged with Harken Energy, an 
Irving, Texas-based corporation that made its mark by buying small 
insolvent companies and making them profitable. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush and his partners got $2 million in stock in the merger and  
he became a consultant and director of Harken. 
</P>
<P>
	It was during his tenure at Harken that Bush's business dealings  
came under increased scrutiny. 
</P>
<P>
	The first incident involved a potentially lucrative offshore  
drilling project in Bahrain awarded in 1990 by the Middle Eastern 
government to Harken, even though the company had never drilled a 
well in water. 
</P>
<P>
	The media were quick to question whether Bahrain was trying to  
curry favor with Bush's father, who was president at the time. 
</P>
<P>
	The younger Bush has denied that accusation, saying he had  
nothing to do with the Bahrain deal. 
</P>
<P>
	Six months later, Bush sold nearly two-thirds of his holdings,  
or $840,000, of stock at $4 a share. A week later the company 
announced a major loss and its stock closed down about 40 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The sale was investigated by the Securities and Exchange  
Commission as possible insider trading. No action was brought 
against Bush. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush said he sold the shares to repay a loan he had taken to  
invest in the Texas Rangers baseball team in 1989. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush had had an inside track in the Rangers deal because of his  
acquaintance with majority owner Eddie Chiles, a family friend 
since Bush was in elementary school. 
</P>
<P>
	Another friend, Bill DeWitt Jr., was a partner with Bush. They  
had known each other from working together at Spectrum. 
</P>
<P>
	The original deal was nixed because the baseball commissioner  
said there was not enough local money in the offer. Bush persuaded 
a competing investment group to join his own and the new offer was 
accepted. He personally bought 1.8 percent of the club as managing 
general partner for $600,000. 
</P>
<P>
	When the team was sold last year to Dallas financier Tom Hicks,  
Bush received about $15 million -- more than 20 times his original 
investment. 
</P>
<P>
	In the years since he was elected governor, his financial  
investments have been in a state blind trust, according to Ms. 
Hughes. 
</P>
<P>
	Now that he has running for president he has filed to create a  
federal blind trust, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Blind trusts are set up to manage funds without investor input  
to assure no ethical conflicts. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
