<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hamilton, McElroy Happy With Mets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- One year ago, Darryl Hamilton was in Chicago with  
the San Francisco Giants at the trading deadline and was dealt to 
the Colorado Rockies. 
</P>
<P>
	Hamilton marked the anniversary Sunday by switching uniforms  
again, joining the New York Mets as part of a five-player deal that 
highlighted a busy day for general manager Steve Phillips. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is obviously a good deal for me,'' said Hamilton, who  
started in center field Sunday against the Chicago Cubs. ``I've got 
the opportunity to go to the playoffs. I don't want to say anything 
negative about my former teammates but I was on a sinking ship. 
It's good to be in a situation where you're playing for 
something.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Colorado traded Hamilton and left-handed reliever Chuck McElroy  
to the Mets for outfielder Brian McRae and two minor leaguers. New 
York also acquired right-hander Billy Taylor from Oakland for 
pitchers Jason Isringhausen and Greg McMichael, and got infielder 
Shawon Dunston from St. Louis for minor league infielder Craig 
Paquette. 
</P>
<P>
	Taylor, who had 26 saves and a 3.98 ERA, was expected to join  
the Mets by gametime Sunday. Dunston was not expected until Monday, 
Phillips said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going for it,'' Phillips said. ``Now's the time. You  
don't know how many times the opportunity will present itself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Phillips wanted to add veteran players for the stretch run.  
</P>
<P>
	``There's a direct correlation between the average age of a team  
and winning,'' he said. ``I don't mean to say if you get all old 
guys that you'll win, but that experience helps. Down the stretch, 
we wanted more veteran players to complement the team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hamilton, 34, is playing for his fifth team in five years.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's a lot different this year than last year,'' he said.  
``This helps my psyche a lot. Last year, I was questioning myself 
as a player.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McElroy, 31, was a questionable addition because he had listed  
New York as a city he did not want to be traded to. The reason? 
</P>
<P>
	``Taxes,'' McElroy said. ``My agent worked something out with  
(the Mets).'' 
</P>
<P>
	New York was never on Hamilton's ``no trade'' list.  
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think there's any place I'd rather be in a pennant  
race than New York,'' said Hamilton, who was hitting .303. ``New 
York is the epitome of major league baseball with the Yankees and 
the Mets.'' 
</P>
<P>
	McElroy was 3-1 with a 6.20 ERA in 41 games with the Rockies. He  
had a 2.90 ERA in 78 games last season and Phillips blamed the 
higher numbers this year on what he called the ``Colorado 
syndrome.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Our sense is that with our infield and team defense, he just  
has to put it over the plate,'' Phillips said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
