<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tepid Mississippi Elections Heat Up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHILADELPHIA, Miss. (AP) -- When Gov. Kirk Fordice stepped up to  
the podium at the Neshoba County Fair last week, the crowd hoped 
for a fiery speech. 
</P>
<P>
	But, like Mississippi's campaign for governor, it was a  
lackluster Fordice who bid farewell to a state that has both 
embraced his businesslike approach to government and recoiled at 
his soap opera-like love life. 
</P>
<P>
	Tuesday, voters will begin the primary process of picking party  
nominees to replace Fordice, who is ineligible to serve a third 
term. 
</P>
<P>
	``In Mississippi we've always enjoyed robust, rambunctious  
politics, but there's not a rambunctious one in the bunch this 
year. It's so bland,'' said David Sansing, a retired University of 
Mississippi historian. ``This is the dullest political campaign in 
my memory. There's a quality of all the same politicians in a 
herd.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Candidates for the governor's job -- eight Democrats and six  
Republicans -- have espoused almost identical platforms of better 
public schools, improved crime-fighting and lower taxes. Family 
values is a popular topic. 
</P>
<P>
	Desperate to pump last-minute life in their campaigns, the  
candidates are turning to zinger commercials. 
</P>
<P>
	The frontrunners -- incumbent Democratic lieutenant governor,  
Ronnie Musgrove, and a former Republican congressman, Mike Parker -- 
both have been battered by hard-hitting television ads. 
</P>
<P>
	Musgrove has been taken to task for running up $200,000 in  
expenses in private state airplanes for trips over the past four 
years. The lawyer also is blamed in late-produced ads for the state 
Legislature's failure to pass a tax cut. 
</P>
<P>
	A 42-year-old father of two, Musgrove has set the campaign pace,  
generally ignoring ads from his strongest opponent in the 
Democratic primary, Jimmy Roberts, a former state Supreme Court 
justice. The latest polls show him with more than a 50 percentage 
points lead over Roberts, 54, and other relatively unknown 
Democrats. 
</P>
<P>
	Parker, 49, who is leading in GOP polls, is being targeted by  
former Lt. Gov. Eddie Briggs, who says Parker's 10 years in 
Congress were unremarkable and that his voting record was liberal. 
</P>
<P>
	In return, Briggs' stand on abortion is questioned in radio ads  
run on behalf of Parker. 
</P>
<P>
	At the Neshoba County Fair near Philadelphia, the most high  
profile of the state's campaign stops, one candidate said he would 
put Musgrove in prison for abusing the airplane privileges. A 
second said Musgrove supporters should ``have their heads 
examined'' and a third said he might shoot him. 
</P>
<P>
	For most of the summer, however, the campaigns have been  
overshadowed by Fordice's surprise June announcement that he was 
divorcing the first lady to marry his childhood sweetheart. The 
Fordices are still living together. 
</P>
<P>
	Mississippi has not had an open governor's seat since 1987 and  
Fordice, the first Republican governor in the state since 
Reconstruction, has not endorsed any of the GOP candidates. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
