<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 18:25:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> PBS To Halt Donor List Exchanges </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PASADENA, Calif. (AP) -- PBS stations will halt all exchanges of  
donor lists with partisan groups within a week, but when the 
political fallout for public broadcasting might end is difficult to 
predict, PBS president Ervin S. Duggan said Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	``By the end of this week, no station in America will be engaged  
in these practices,'' Duggan told a meeting of the Television 
Critics Association. 
</P>
<P>
	``It has delayed the (federal budget) authorization process and  
I don't know what the outcome will be,'' he said. ``I hope we can 
put it behind us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Of the 349 public television stations nationwide, PBS has  
admitted that as many as 30 appear to have engaged in list rentals 
or exchanges with political groups. 
</P>
<P>
	At issue is whether the list-swapping constitutes a violation of  
federal tax law. Tax experts have said that such exchanges would 
not be a violation as long as all political parties receives equal 
access to the lists. 
</P>
<P>
	The issue came to light in May, when Boston station WGBH-TV  
admitted giving a list of donors' names to the Democratic National 
Committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Although he condemned the practice, Duggan said outside list  
brokers working for PBS stations swapped names with both Republican 
and Democratic groups. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is nonpolitical and nonpartisan behavior,'' Duggan said,  
noting that Bob Dole's 1996 presidential campaign and the 
conservative think tank Heritage Foundation were among those 
involved in swaps. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked if the issue was being used by PBS critics as a weapon  
against public broadcasting, he replied carefully. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not going to deal with the motives of people on Capitol  
Hill or what might seem to some an effort to expand this issue 
beyond its proper limits,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Federal funding could be withheld from stations -- which get 25  
percent of their money from direct-mail appeals -- but that would be 
an overreaction because it was clear they intended to cooperate, he 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	In Washington, the House Commerce Committee was scheduled to  
consider funding for the Corporation for Public Broadcasting on 
July 14 but postponed the meeting after the mailing list 
disclosures. 
</P>
<P>
	Two lawmakers -- Rep. Billy Tauzin, R-La., chairman of the  
committee's telecommunications subcommittee, and Rep. Christopher 
Cox, R-Calif. -- have asked for investigations into the practice. 
</P>
<P>
	Tauzin, who was sponsoring the funding authorization bill for  
PBS, said he will reduce his funding proposal. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990801.0110 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 18:50:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> California Rower Reaches Australia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRISBANE, Australia (AP) -- An American who is trying to row solo  
around the world said Monday he was relieved to have reached 
Australia. 
</P>
<P>
	Mick Bird of Malibu, Calif., arrived Sunday in Cairns, a resort  
town on the northeast coast of Australia's Queensland state, after 
more than 12 months at sea. 
</P>
<P>
	Bird began his trip from Fort Bragg, Calif., on Aug. 19, 1997,  
in his 26-foot rowboat ``Reach.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He completed the first leg of his planned 27,000-mile journey by  
reaching Hilo, Hawaii, in October 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	For the latest leg, he left the Marshall Islands in April and  
said his normal routine was to row 10 hours a day. 
</P>
<P>
	Bird said when he left the Marshall Islands he was uncertain  
whether ocean currents would sweep him to Australia, Papua New 
Guinea or Indonesia. 
</P>
<P>
	Bird said he was excited when he realized he had reached the  
Queensland coast. ``I could feel the butterflies in my stomach, or 
maybe I was just hungry,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Another adventurer, Englishman Andrew Halsey, is also attempting  
to row across the Pacific Ocean. He left San Diego July 15 and is 
currently 550 miles west of the West Coast. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990801.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 18:00:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Griffey Mum on Piniella Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SEATTLE (AP) -- Ken Griffey Jr. doesn't want to talk about his  
future with the Seattle Mariners. But his father, Ken Sr., the 
bench coach with the Cincinnati Reds, is doing a lot of talking for 
him. 
</P>
<P>
	``Do I look like I'm in Dayton?'' the Mariners' slugger said  
when asked about a story in Sunday's editions of the Dayton Daily 
News that said the Mariners were in a mood to fire manager Lou 
Piniella and replace him with Griffey Sr. 
</P>
<P>
	Griffey Sr. told the Dayton newspaper, ``That might be the only  
way to keep Junior. He said he's gone.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't read what you all write,'' Griffey said after  
Seattle's 3-1 victory over Baltimore. ``I'm not in Dayton.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mariners president Chuck Armstrong said he had no reaction to  
the Dayton story. 
</P>
<P>
	``Lou is signed through 2000,'' Armstrong said before walking  
away from a reporter. 
</P>
<P>
	Griffey, 29, leads the American League with 34 home runs and has  
384 career homers. He is signed through the 2000 season and the 
Mariners have said they want to sign him to a contract extension. 
</P>
<P>
	Griffey is believed to be unhappy with the Mariners' new Safeco  
Field, where he has two homers in his first 11 games in the 
ballpark. He hit 198 of his homers in the Kingdome, which the 
Mariners left after a game June 27. 
</P>
<P>
	He has said he's unhappy with the Mariners' lack of pitching.  
The Mariners have the worst ERA in the AL at 5.81. 
</P>
<P>
	Griffey had a rare bad defensive day Sunday. He lost two fly  
balls in the sun in the sixth inning when the Orioles scored their 
only run off the Mariners. Both were ruled hits. 
</P>
<P>
	He was not in an expansive mood about that subject, either.  
</P>
<P>
	``I don't want to talk about that,'' the nine-time Gold Glove  
center fielder said. ``You all saw it.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
