<HEADLINE> Four Die in Ohio Plane Crash </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NORTH LIMA, Ohio (AP) -- A single-engine plane crashed in a  
cornfield just after takeoff Sunday, killing four of the five 
people aboard, authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
	The fifth person, a 15-year-old boy, was hospitalized in serious  
condition at Cleveland MetroHealth Medical Center, a nursing 
supervisor said. No names were released. 
</P>
<P>
	The six-seater Piper Cherokee's flight originated in Oshkosh,  
Wis., and was headed to Pennsylvania when it crashed at about 2 
p.m. a half-mile north of the airfield in North Lima, where it had 
stopped to refuel, said state Highway Patrol Lt. Brian Girts. 
</P>
<P>
	North Lima is 66 miles southeast of Cleveland.  
</P>
<P>
	The Federal Aviation Authority was investigating and had not  
determined the cause of the crash. 
</P>
<P>
	The crash occurred about 150 miles southeast of Cottrellville  
Township, Mich., the site of a small plane crash Saturday that 
killed a group of nine skydivers and the pilot. The plane in 
Michigan also crashed shortly after takeoff. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
