<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 14:10:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Family Copes As Umpire Is Released </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Betsy Hallion and her three boys kept looking out the window.  
</P>
<P>
	They knew baseball was releasing 13 National League umpires by  
letter via Federal Express. What they didn't know was whether Dad, 
Tom Hallion, was on the hit list. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were on pins and needles all day,'' she said by telephone  
from her home in Louisville, Ky. ``Every time a truck came down the 
street, you wondered. It was driving the kids crazy. It was driving 
me crazy.'' 
</P>
<P>
	By mid-afternoon Thursday, the anxiety had become too much. So  
with her husband still on the field at Veterans Stadium, she 
rounded up 13-year-old Corey, 10-year-old Kyle and 3-year-old Jake 
and got in the car. 
</P>
<P>
	``We came back at 5:30 and there was nothing from FedEx. No  
letter,'' she said, her tears gone. ``We thought we were safe.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hallion called a half-hour later from the airport in  
Philadelphia. 
</P>
<P>
	``I asked him, `Well, what is it?' He said, `I lost my job.'''  
</P>
<P>
	The final out.  
</P>
<P>
	At 42, Hallion had spent more than half his life as a  
professional umpire. Rated as one of the majors' best in a players' 
poll -- taken before his three-game suspension this year -- he joined 
other umps in a recent mass resignation plan. 
</P>
<P>
	But the ploy backfired when baseball hired minor leaguers to  
replace them starting in September. In all, the resignations of 22 
major league umps were accepted, including Hallion's. 
</P>
<P>
	``We soul-searched for two days when it was presented,'' Mrs.  
Hallion said. ``I said to him, `Are you ready for the worst?' All 
he ever wanted to be was an umpire.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We didn't think we were jumping off a cliff,'' she said.  
</P>
<P>
	It has turned into an emotional, bitter fight among a group of  
men who stood together for years and now have split apart over 
umpires' union chief Richie Phillips' leadership. 
</P>
<P>
	Even umpires' wives have entered the fray -- one wife angrily  
chastised another whose husband did not turn in his resignation, 
calling him a ``Judas'' for turning his back on the union. 
</P>
<P>
	Hallion was headed for a 12-hour stopover in Louisville when he  
phoned Betsy. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't know how to tell her,'' he said Friday night in  
Milwaukee, where he worked the Brewers-Montreal game. ``I called 
three people first to see how I should do it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Afterward, his wife said, ``I cried all day. It was probably the  
worst day of our lives.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``People were calling the house,'' Hallion said. ``How do you  
tell them why you were one of the 13?'' 
</P>
<P>
	He is sure he was targeted for bumping Colorado catcher Jeff  
Reed and coach Milt May in June, which led to Hallion's suspension. 
</P>
<P>
	For the Hallions, it all means coming to grips with the loss of  
the only life they'd known. There's also his salary of $160,000, 
including bonuses. That's a far cry from the minors, when fancy 
dinners meant all-you-can-eat salad bars and hotels meant $9 rooms. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would like to be able to stay in this house because this is  
where the boys grew up,'' Mrs. Hallion said. ``But there will be 
lifestyle changes. 
</P>
<P>
	``We hope this is not over,'' she said. ``But if this is the  
end, there will be life without baseball.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Hallion, who does not work now, plans to do computer work  
out of her home. Her husband has had offers, she said, but declined 
to be specific. 
</P>
<P>
	They married in September 1983 and the following month were sent  
to work winter ball in the Dominican Republic. Sweethearts from 
upstate Saugerties, N.Y., they left friends and family behind and 
moved to Louisville in March 1984. 
</P>
<P>
	``We didn't know a soul,'' she said. ``We picked it when he was  
in the American Association because it was centrally located. It 
gave us a chance to see each other for a few hours when he was 
going between cities.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The next year, Hallion worked his first NL game. In 1986, after  
eight seasons of stops in the New York-Penn, Carolina and Eastern 
leagues and the American Association, he joined the NL staff. 
</P>
<P>
	For a major league umpire, the travel, money and prestige are  
satisfying, no doubt. But the job also means long separations, and 
missed birthday parties and Little League games. 
</P>
<P>
	Umps have no home games.  
</P>
<P>
	Corey and Kyle grew up watching their father work, visiting the  
umpires' locker rooms and sitting up proud when they saw him on TV. 
Mrs. Hallion is sad that Jake, the youngest, may miss out on that. 
</P>
<P>
	And she's disappointed her husband may not fulfill his lifelong  
dream to call a World Series game -- he may have been in line to do 
it this year. She's concerned he might feel he did not do a good 
job, even though the players' rating shows otherwise. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want people to know he was a good umpire, and that he cared  
about being the best he could be,'' she said. ``This job was so 
important to him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And it all ended with a letter from baseball.  
</P>
<P>
	That letter, by the way, eventually arrived at the Hallion  
household. The following day. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990801.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 16:10:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Favre Joins Packers' Camp </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	GREEN BAY, Wis. (AP) -- Brett Favre may have looked a little  
rusty in his 1999 training camp debut, but his presence was 
welcomed. 
</P>
<P>
	Favre, who missed the first days of camp while in Mississippi  
with his wife and their baby, arrived Saturday and went through a 
Sunday morning workout of more than two hours with his teammates. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was good to have Brett Favre back here,'' coach Ray Rhodes  
said. ``Brett brings a lot of spark to our offensive unit and 
that's big for our football team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Favre's second daughter, Breleigh Ann, was born five weeks  
premature July 13 in Hattiesburg, Miss., and was in a hospital 
until Thursday. 
</P>
<P>
	Quarterbacks Rick Mirer, Matt Hasselbeck, Aaron Brooks and  
Ronnie McAda picked up the slack for the three-time MVP while he 
was gone. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a little rusty but we love to have him back,'' offensive  
coordinator Sherm Lewis said. ``It looks great to have him in there 
and I think the guys feel good when he's there. I think he was a 
little rusty throwing the ball, but that's it.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
