<DOCNO> APW19990801.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 13:10:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lee Denies Giving China Secrets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Declaring his innocence, the scientist  
suspected of passing vital U.S. nuclear weapons secrets to the 
Chinese said Sunday it was common practice for scientists to 
transfer secret information from classified to unclassified 
computers. 
</P>
<P>
	``The truth is I'm innocent,'' Wen Ho Lee said in an interview  
with CBS' ``60 Minutes'' aired Sunday. ``Suddenly, they told me I'm 
a traitor. ... I just don't understand this.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Energy Secretary Bill Richardson, interviewed on the same  
program, said such a transfer, which would have made it easier for 
the Chinese to gain access to the information, was ``wrong and 
improper.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``He violated our national security procedure at Los Alamos as a  
government employee of the United States,'' Richardson said. ``This 
is something that we are not going to tolerate.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lee was fired in the spring from his security sensitive job at  
the Energy Department's lab in Los Alamos, N.M., after he had been 
under investigation for possible espionage since 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	Evidence emerged after his firing that Lee had shifted thousands  
of classified atomic weapons codes to an unsecured computer. 
</P>
<P>
	The Justice Department has not decided whether to charge Lee  
with any crime. 
</P>
<P>
	In the interview, Lee said he said he used three passwords on  
his unsecured computer so ``it's almost impossible for anybody to 
break in. You know, sometimes I even had a hard time to break in 
myself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Asked why he was singled out for the espionage investigation,  
Lee said his best explanation was that authorities needed a 
scapegoat and as a Chinese person born in Taiwan ``they think I'm 
perfect for them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lee, an American citizen since 1974, came under scrutiny after  
it became evident that the Chinese may have acquired secret design 
information about the W-88 nuclear warhead. Lee worked on that 
project and had made several trips to China. 
</P>
<P>
	Richardson denied Lee was being made a scapegoat. ``This man  
massively violated our security procedures at Los Alamos,'' he 
said, referring to improper contacts with Chinese officials and 
violations of security rules by his transfer of secret data to 
unclassifed computers. 
</P>
<P>
	The Los Angeles Times reported Sunday that a legal brief Lee's  
lawyers submitted to the Justice Department stressed that Lee had 
``used considerable care'' to protect the security of nuclear codes 
he moved to an unclassified computer. 
</P>
<P>
	His attorneys argued that Lee had good reason to transfer the  
files, because it was easier to work outside the classified system 
and the extra file provided a backup in case of computer 
breakdowns. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Orrin Hatch, chairman of the Senate Judiciary Committee,  
said Sunday that charging Lee with mishandling classified material 
might be appropriate because ``it is very difficult to prove 
espionage.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hatch, who is seeking the Republican nomination for president,  
also said on ``Fox News Sunday'' that the Justice Department 
mishandled the case. 
</P>
<P>
	Hatch, R-Utah, said Attorney General Janet Reno refused FBI  
requests for warrants against Lee even though the scientist had 
waived his rights and a warrant was not required. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's what really is mind-boggling to those of us who really  
look at this,'' the senator said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990801.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 12:36:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Mets Get Dunston for Paquette </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- The New York Mets picked up veteran infielder  
Shawon Dunston from the St. Louis Cardinals just before the trading 
deadline Saturday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Dunston, who broke out of an 0-for-24 slump with two hits  
Saturday, is batting .307 with five homers and 25 RBIs in 150 
at-bats. He cost the Mets minor league infielder Craig Paquette, 
30, who was assigned to Triple-A Memphis. 
</P>
<P>
	``Dunston serves in a multi-purpose role,'' Mets general manager  
Steve Phillips said. ``He can come off the bench and hit. We look 
for him to be a nice veteran addition.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dunston, 36, wasn't happy as he cleaned out his locker with two  
of his children. He said he didn't know if he would join the Mets, 
his sixth team in three years, right away. 
</P>
<P>
	``I thought I found a home here, but that's how it goes,'' he  
said. ``I'm not really surprised about this. It's not like it's the 
first time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Dunston has been a shortstop most of his career, but has also  
played some outfield the last few years. 
</P>
<P>
	Paquette is currently with the U.S. Pan American team. He hit a  
two-run home run Thursday in an upset of Cuba in Winnipeg. 
</P>
<P>
	In six major-league seasons, Paquette has a career .232 batting  
average with 55 homers and 195 RBIs in 426 games. In 1998 he batted 
.263 in seven games with the Mets, and in 70 games for Triple-A 
Norfolk this year he batted .272 with 15 homers and 54 RBIs. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
