<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Olivia Newton-John Performs in Nev. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RENO, Nev. (AP) -- Olivia Newton-John says her body was content  
to kick back and relax after her 1992 triumph over breast cancer. 
Her mind, however, didn't like running in neutral. 
</P>
<P>
	``I kept waking up at night with songs in my head,'' the singer  
told a sold-out casino crowd Saturday night. 
</P>
<P>
	That led to her album ``Gaia: One Woman's Journey,'' which also  
is the title of her first tour since she was diagnosed with breast 
cancer. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm really very, very lucky. I treasure every day,'' she told  
a cheering audience that responded with three standing ovations. 
</P>
<P>
	The two-hour performance included her Grease-era hits like  
``Please Mr. Please,'' ``Have You Never Been Mellow?'' and 1974's 
``I Honestly Love You'' that she re-recorded on last year's ``Back 
With a Heart'' album. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
