<DOCNO> APW19990801.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 15:10:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cowboys Adjust Without Sanders, Lett </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WICHITA FALLS, Texas (AP) -- The Dallas Cowboys are going through  
training camp without their two best defenders, Deion Sanders and 
Leon Lett. They better get used to playing without them. 
</P>
<P>
	Sanders is recovering from toe surgery and Lett is suspended for  
failing yet another drug test. The team has no idea when either 
will be back; there's a good chance neither will suit up before 
October. 
</P>
<P>
	So with their preseason opener a week away and the regular  
season beginning Sept. 12, all the Cowboys can do is wait. 
</P>
<P>
	``We just coach the guys who are here,'' coach Chan Gailey said.  
``We work with the things we can control.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sanders is with the team at Midwestern State University,  
continuing the rehabilitation on his rebuilt left big toe. He's 
allowed to jog straight ahead and he's even playing some 
basketball, which forces him to flex his toes and put pressure on 
them. 
</P>
<P>
	Sanders attends every practice wearing a red do-rag with  
``Jesus'' across the forehead. He walks around giving tips to the 
cornerbacks and occasionally helps on coverage drills by rifling 
left-handed passes. 
</P>
<P>
	``Deion, we've got to have you,'' a fan yelled to him Friday.  
``We're praying for you.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Yet the Cowboys have no idea when he'll be back.  
</P>
<P>
	``We're all very curious,'' Cowboys owner Jerry Jones said.  
``It's looking good, but that's all we know.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sanders is the most vital piece of the Dallas defense. When he  
lines up at cornerback, quarterbacks ignore his side of the field, 
giving teammates a smaller area to defend. He's also the NFL's most 
electrifying punt returner. 
</P>
<P>
	Proof of Sanders' impact can be found in Dallas' record last  
year: 8-3 with him, 2-3 without him. 
</P>
<P>
	But Sanders needs his toes to be healthy for him to be at his  
best because his game is based on his feet -- quick cuts, flashy 
moves and breakaway speed. 
</P>
<P>
	``We need to make sure it's healed so we can have him for a long  
period of time,'' Gailey said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cowboys play twice in September, including a Monday night  
game against Atlanta in the second week. That prime time outing 
against Sanders' former club could be a target date. 
</P>
<P>
	But with Dallas off the next week, he's more likely to return  
Oct. 3 against Arizona, especially with the Cowboys trying to 
avenge a playoff loss to the Cardinals. 
</P>
<P>
	``If he comes back, then that's going to be a great, great  
plus,'' said Kevin Smith, who was benched last year but will start 
in Sanders' place. ``If he doesn't, we just have to get the job 
done.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lett, the anchor of Dallas' defensive line, is suspended  
indefinitely for his third violations of the NFL's substance abuse 
program. His previous penalties were predetermined, but this one is 
up to NFL commissioner Paul Tagliabue. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cowboys are hoping to be Lett-less for only four games  
because that's how long Tagliabue punished the last three-time 
violator, Clayton Holmes. Under that time frame, Lett would return 
Oct. 10 in Philadelphia. 
</P>
<P>
	But two months after Lett's suspension, Tagliabue has yet to  
even say when he'll make a decision. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's nothing abnormal about that,'' said Jones, who had  
hoped to know before camp opened last week. ``It doesn't in any way 
cause me any more concern.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lett, who missed 19 games between 1995-97 because of  
drug-related suspensions, played in every game last season for the 
first time since 1994. Both years, he was picked to play in the Pro 
Bowl. 
</P>
<P>
	Michael Myers is penciled in as Lett's replacement at tackle  
even though he played defensive end as a rookie last year. There's 
little depth behind him and fellow starter Chad Hennings. 
</P>
<P>
	``Not having Leon Lett is a takeaway as far as our team is  
concerned,'' Jones said. ``But I feel better after our first five 
practices than I felt coming to camp about what we're going to do 
if Leon is not playing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Lett has returned from his previous suspensions in good shape  
and has always contributed immediately. Coaches hope that's the 
case again. 
</P>
<P>
	``If he gets here, when he gets here, we'll work him and try to  
get him ready to play,'' Gailey said, ``because we know what he can 
do.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
