<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 1 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Heat Wave Death Toll Reaches 150  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Medical authorities in Chicago will be examining  
the bodies of 20 people today to see if they are additional victims 
of a deadly heat wave. At least 50 people in Illinois have died as 
a result of the heat since the high temperatures settled in on July 
19. They're among at least 150 heat-related deaths around the 
country. Temperatures have cooled in the Windy City, with highs 
yesterday in the 80s and more of the same expected today. A city 
spokesman says there are still some lingering effects from the 
heat, including some power outages. 

</P>
<P>
	Bradley: Taiwan Should Temper Talk  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The United States must make clear that Taiwan  
should not expect U.S. aid if Taiwan's unilateral moves toward 
independence provoke a Chinese invasion, Democratic presidential 
candidate Bill Bradley said today. Bradley, who is challenging Vice 
President Al Gore for the Democratic nomination, told NBC ``we 
would be there'' if China takes military action against Taiwan 
without a move toward independence. Separately, Bradley said he was 
``actually shocked that the Gore campaign attacked me so strongly'' 
after Bradley urged candidates for president to decline ``soft 
money'' contributions -- the largely unregulated donations to 
political parties. 

</P>
<P>
	Palestinian Factions Seek Reconcilion  
</P>
<P>
	CAIRO, Egypt (AP) -- PLO factions that have been bitterly opposed  
for years moved toward reconciliation today, saying they needed the 
strength of unity in the last stage of negotiations with Israel. 
But during their meeting in Cairo, it was clear it will not be easy 
to heal the rifts between PLO chairman Yasser Arafat and his 
rivals. Representatives of Arafat's Fatah faction and those of the 
Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine were upbeat after a 
three-hour morning session in Cairo, their first encounter since 
Arafat signed a peace accord with Israel in Oslo in 1993. 

</P>
<P>
	Service for Mrs. Barton To Be Held  
</P>
<P>
	LIZELLE, Ga. (AP) -- The wife of mass killer Mark Barton will be  
buried today. Leigh Ann Barton was the first person killed in her 
husband's rampage through the Atlanta area last week. He went on to 
kill eleven others, including his two children, before committing 
suicide. So far, two of the nine brokerage victims have been laid 
to rest: 48-year-old Charles Tenenbaum and 52-year-old Dean 
Delawalla. Last week's massacre was the bloodiest mass killing in 
Atlanta's history. 

</P>
<P>
	Tiananmen Protester Heads to U.S.  
</P>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- A Chinese dissident sheltered by U.S. diplomats  
for four months after he fled to Russia to escape arrest has flown 
on to the United States, a human rights group and exiled dissidents 
said today. Xie Wanjun, a former leader of the 1989 Tiananmen 
Square democracy protests, arrived in New York yesterday evening, 
said the Hong Kong-based Information Center of Human Rights and 
Democratic Movement in China. Xie, fled China in April and was 
granted refuge by the U.S. Consulate in the Russian port of 
Vladivostok. The consulate sheltered him for four months, while 
China pressured Russia for Xie's return. 

</P>
<P>
	Iran Re-Arrests German Businessman  
</P>
<P>
	DUBAI, United Arab Emirates (AP) -- Iranian police re-arrested a  
German businessman who was condemned to death for illicit sex and 
later released on bail, a judicial spokesman said today. Helmut 
Hofer was taken back into custody today for fear he was planning to 
flee the country after he was released in April ahead of a retrial, 
the official Islamic Republic News Agency quoted the official as 
saying. Hofer, 54, was convicted in January 1998 of having sexual 
relations with a 26-year-old Iranian woman outside of marriage. 

</P>
<P>
	Albanian Concert Held in Kosovo  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Waving flags and dancing in front of  
their seats, tens of thousands of ethnic Albanians packed 
Pristina's sports stadium today for an Albanian music festival. The 
concert, featuring 38 Albanian artists from Serbia's majority 
Albanian province, as well as neighboring Macedonia and Albania, 
was organized by Enver Idrizi, the 1994 world karate champion. 
Proceeds from the tickets, which sold for $2.75, will go toward a 
sports institute in Kosovo. 

</P>
<P>
	Report: Jazz To Sign Malone for $67M  
</P>
<P>
	SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- The Utah Jazz reportedly will sign  
two-time NBA MVP Karl Malone to a four-year contract worth the 
maximum $67 million under NBA salary cap rules. The Salt Lake 
Tribune reported the pending contract, and Malone as well as Jazz 
owner Larry Miller confirmed for the Associated Press that a press 
conference is planned for today to announce Malone's re-signing. 
Malone averaged 23.8 points in 1999, his lowest since 1986-87, his 
second year in the league. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by DAVID GOODMAN  
  	   	
