<DOCNO> APW19990801.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 11:20:20 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Casino Competition Rises in Detroit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- If there's a sign that competition has come to  
the market for Detroit's gambling dollars, it's the billboard over 
freeways leading into Detroit that reads ``Tax Free Winnings In 
Canada!'' 
</P>
<P>
	The ad campaign is one of several moves by Canada's Casino  
Windsor to entice the majority of its customers who come from the 
United States to keep making the trip to Windsor, Ontario, just 
across the river from Detroit. 
</P>
<P>
	Windsor and some of Michigan's Indian casinos are turning up  
their marketing efforts to lure customers back once the newness 
wears off the MGM Grand Detroit Casino. But the casinos are also 
counting on competition to grow the number of people coming to the 
Detroit area with a few bucks they're willing to lay on the table. 
</P>
<P>
	``Competition makes people much better at what they do,'' said  
MGM Grand Inc. Chairman J. Terrence Lanni. ``If you become a 
monopoly, you become fat, dumb and happy, and we don't want to do 
that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Casino Windsor has had a near monopoly on gamblers in the  
Detroit area since it opened in 1994 within a five-minute drive of 
downtown Detroit. In 1998, Windsor pulled in 20,000 customers a day 
and earned $535 million; 80 percent of those visitors were from the 
United States. 
</P>
<P>
	Some gamblers who made it in to the MGM Grand opening Thursday  
said they were likely to cut back on visits to Canada. Henry Perry 
of Mount Clemens waited 4 1/2 hours to get in Thursday, just to feel 
the excitement of opening day. Perry said he's been to most of the 
casinos in Michigan and to Casino Windsor. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's about as good as any I've been to. Maybe even a few steps  
better,'' Perry said while waiting to play a slot machine. ``I 
probably won't go back to Windsor much. Here, you don't have to be 
bothered with getting your money exchanged.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Casino Windsor spokesman Jim Mundy said any decline in  
attendance will be temporary. 
</P>
<P>
	``We certainly expect to see a drop in attendance, as people  
check out MGM and see what it has to offer,'' Mundy said. ``But 
then there'll be a rebound.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mundy said Windsor offers more amenities -- a 389-room attached  
hotel, four restaurants, and space for live acts. 
</P>
<P>
	Perhaps more important, Mundy said, Americans benefit from using  
Canadian money because the exchange rate -- about $1.50 Canadian for 
every $1 American -- gives gamblers more to play with. 
</P>
<P>
	Casino Windsor's billboards have drawn some criticism from MGM  
Grand officials, who contend the message is misleading. While 
gambling winnings are not taxed in Canada, Americans who bring 
their winnings back must report them on their income taxes. 
</P>
<P>
	Mundy said the sign was not meant to mislead and is ``completely  
true.'' 
</P>
<P>
	With the arrival of MGM, the nearest Indian casino to Detroit,  
the Soaring Eagle Casino and Resort in Mount Pleasant, has also 
turned to Detroit freeway billboards for promotion and has started 
bringing in higher-tier entertainers, such as Ray Charles and Kenny 
Rogers, said spokesman Bill Masterson. 
</P>
<P>
	The casino in central Michigan is a 2 1/2-hour drive away, but  
offers a 512-room hotel, indoor and outdoor pools, an art gallery 
and even a child care center. 
</P>
<P>
	Like Windsor, Soaring Eagle has a size advantage over the MGM  
Grand Detroit, which is limited by the city to 75,000 square feet 
of gambling area. MGM Grand has 2,370 slots, while Windsor has 
2,947 and Soaring Eagle has over 4,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Masterson said MGM Grand is not a long-term threat.  
</P>
<P>
	``Whenever something new opens people are drawn to it,''  
Masterson said. ``We think over time, and even a relatively short 
period of time, our business will be back. We believe we're a 
destination resort, and it's based not on glitter and bells. It's 
based on arts and culture.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Experts disagree about Windsor's chances of holding onto its  
customers. Todd Jordan, an industry analyst with Raymond James &AMP; 
Associates Inc., said Casino Windsor would have a tough time. 
</P>
<P>
	``Location means a lot in this business, and unfortunately their  
location is at a disadvantage,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	But Bill Thompson, a professor at the University of Nevada-Las  
Vegas and a gambling industry expert, said Windsor would keep more 
than its fair share of a market where most of the gamblers live 
within 50 miles of Detroit. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think there's still a fear of going to downtown Detroit,''  
he said. ``People in Ann Arbor and Flint can get to Windsor just as 
easily as they can get to casinos in Detroit.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Others say the increased competition could pay off for all  
players, as the region's gambling market grows to as much as $1.5 
billion a year. 
</P>
<P>
	``People go to Las Vegas and Atlantic City because they know  
there's more than one casino there,'' Mundy said. ``When people 
outside the immediate market hear there's four casinos in the 
Detroit-Windsor area, the market will begin to grow and it will 
become a gaming destination.'' 

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990801.0139 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 21:50:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Broncos Heading to Australia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- The Denver Broncos don't profess to know much  
Australian history. They're familiar mostly with the basics. 
</P>
<P>
	``They have kangaroos,'' quarterback Bubby Brister said on the  
eve of his team's Sunday night flight to Sydney, Australia, where 
the Broncos will play the San Diego Chargers in an exhibition game. 
</P>
<P>
	``Kangaroos, koalas and the Crocodile Hunter,'' tight end  
Shannon Sharpe said. ``That's about my extent on Australia.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The country that is home to celebrities such as Nicole Kidman,  
Greg Norman, Paul ``Crocodile Dundee'' Hogan and Elle MacPherson 
will play host to its first NFL game, the American Bowl, on Sunday 
at Stadium Australia. 
</P>
<P>
	Getting there doesn't promise to be half the fun.  
</P>
<P>
	The Broncos left Denver at 11 p.m. EDT, about an hour later than  
scheduled. They were flying 2 1/2 hours to Los Angeles before 
embarking upon a 14 1/2-hour flight to Sydney. 
</P>
<P>
	Because of the 16-hour time change, Monday will not exist for  
the players, coaches and accompanying entourage. They were 
scheduled to arrive in Australia on Tuesday morning. 
</P>
<P>
	It's an itinerary only Rip Van Winkle could love.  
</P>
<P>
	``They've told us when to fall asleep,'' defensive end Harald  
Hasselbach said. ``They'll come around and hand out sleeping pills 
if you want them, so by the time you get there, you're 
acclimated.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hasselbach, who has traveled to six continents, will be making  
his third trip to Australia. He was part of the Broncos' advanced 
scouting group that visited Sydney in April. 
</P>
<P>
	He also went Down Under in 1997 after winning a nationwide  
photography contest. 
</P>
<P>
	``I wanted to go because that was the only continent that I  
hadn't visited that's visitable,'' Hasselbach said. ``We loved it. 
Now that we're going again, I look at this as a tremendous 
opportunity.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Still, how does a group of more than 100 people stay sane during  
17 hours in the air? 
</P>
<P>
	``Play cards, watch movies. That's about all you can do,''  
Sharpe said. ``I'll try to sleep, but I'm going to stay up for 
about 12 hours and aggravate everybody.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``He can probably do that,'' running back Terrell Davis said.  
``That's his trademark, being loud on the plane and waking 
everybody up. I hope they put my seat far from his.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Davis, the NFL's reigning MVP, figures to be one of the more  
talented players in Australia this week, but he won't be the most 
popular. 
</P>
<P>
	San Diego punter Darren Bennett is from Australia and the  
Broncos have agreed to sign punter Jon Ballantyne, an Australian 
who played in the NFL Europe League. 
</P>
<P>
	The pair, as well as curiosity, should help fill Stadium  
Australia, a 110,000-seat venue built for the 2000 Summer Olympics. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think they'll like it,'' linebacker Bill Romanowski said.  
``They're big on rugby over there. That's a tough game. You don't 
wear pads. I think they'll like the excitement and the hitting that 
football has to offer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Romanowski will be playing in his sixth American Bowl overall  
and his second with the Broncos, who have played exhibition games 
in London; Tokyo; Berlin; Barcelona, Spain, and Mexico City. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm kind of looking forward to it,'' coach Mike Shanahan said.  
``I'm not sure about the 16-hour flight of actually getting there. 
I think it will break up camp. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm sure there's a couple of vets that'll go out and get a  
chance to see the culture a little bit. I'd like them to do that. I 
think we can get a lot of work done and have them enjoy 
themselves.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
