<DOCNO> APW19990801.0140 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 15:00:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Couple Just Missed Fateful Flight </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	COTTRELLVILLE TOWNSHIP, Mich. (AP) -- Skydivers Bob and Caroline  
Johnson were running late and just missed joining their fellow 
parachutists aboard a weekend flight, and it saved their lives. The 
plane crashed, killing 10. 
</P>
<P>
	The couple, hosting relatives from Florida, showed up late for  
their skydiving appointment at Marine City Airport. They had 
planned to be on Saturday's first flight of the 1967 Beech King Air 
65A-90 -- which veered sharply shortly after takeoff and plummeted 
into a hayfield, exploding into a ball of fire. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a very sad day,'' Bob Johnson, of Rochester Hills, told  
The Detroit News for a report Sunday. ``It's the weekend when we 
all take off from everything else and come out and enjoy each 
other's company and be thankful for all the times we've had. 
</P>
<P>
	``We all know the risk, and it's something we expect. It's  
better than sitting home on the couch, scared of life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Federal investigators planned to remain at the scene for three  
to five days, then return to Washington, D.C., to continue to 
review evidence. A determination of the crash's cause could take as 
long as six months. 
</P>
<P>
	High heat and humidity can make it more difficult for a plane to  
take off. But there were no indications that they were the cause of 
the crash, said George Black, a spokesman for the National 
Transportation Safety Board. 
</P>
<P>
	It was 82 degrees with 69 percent humidity Saturday morning.  
</P>
<P>
	Engine failure does not appear to be a cause, but a final  
determination will wait for testing, Black said. 
</P>
<P>
	It appeared the plane had been properly loaded, an issue that is  
often to blame for small plane crashes, Black said. 
</P>
<P>
	Paul Myks, an experienced commercial pilot who had logged more  
than 9,000 hours of flight time, had prepared a manifest listing 
the weight of each jumper and piece of equipment, and appeared to 
have balanced the weight properly, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The plane did not carry a flight data recorder and was not  
required to do so, Black said. 
</P>
<P>
	The skydivers were part of a group called the Parahawks, who  
flew out of the airport about 40 miles north of Detroit. All those 
who died were veteran skydivers. 
</P>
<P>
	According to the U.S. Parachute Association, 32 people died  
while skydiving last year, one for every 100,000 jumps, The Detroit 
News reported. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990801.0141 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 20:00:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Seahawks' Coach Holmgren Debuts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHENEY, Wash. (AP) -- The Seattle Seahawks got a quick  
introduction to Mike Holmgren's practice philosophy at Sunday's 
opening of training camp. 
</P>
<P>
	Rather than allow the team to ease into camp the first day,  
Holmgren interrupted proceedings midway through a morning session 
and explained to the entire team what he expects to see in 
first-and-10 situations. 
</P>
<P>
	The chat session illustrated the new Seahawks' coach's emphasis  
on detail and his willingness to take time out from practice to 
discuss his philosophy. 
</P>
<P>
	``I want to explain to them what the drill was. I want to  
explain to them what I expect of them,'' said Holmgren, whose 
predecessor, Dennis Erickson, typically took a more hands-off 
approach in practice. 
</P>
<P>
	According to All-Pro defensive end Michael Sinclair, Holmgren  
has made a strong early impression on Seahawks players. 
</P>
<P>
	``When we first came to camp, he explained his philosophy,''  
said Sinclair, starting his ninth year with the team. ``He just 
said, `We're going to pay more attention to details. Because if you 
can't do the little things, then you can't play for me.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Added Ricky Watters, ``With coach Holmgren, we're going to be  
very disciplined.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But, Watters said, Holmgren's discipline also has a soft side.  
</P>
<P>
	``Coach Holmgren is always positive,'' the running back said.  
``Even when something goes wrong he's still positive about it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Holmgren, the former Green Bay Packers coach who took over in  
Seattle after Erickson was fired following an 8-8 season, is trying 
to get the Seahawks to the playoffs for the first time since 1988. 
</P>
<P>
	He liked what he saw Sunday.  
</P>
<P>
	``This was a good day. This is fun,'' he said. ``You see a  
little bit of the rust, but you also see great enthusiasm and great 
effort.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For Holmgren, seeing his players take the field was a reward for  
the months of preparations leading up to camp. 
</P>
<P>
	``Once we get out on the field, there's not a lot of  
paperwork,'' he said. ``It's just football, so it's fun.'' 
</P>
<P>
                              *Eagles    	
</P>
<P>
	The fans who booed him on the day he was drafted cheered Donovan  
McNabb on his first day of training camp with Philadelphia. 
</P>
<P>
	McNabb, taken with the second overall pick in the April 17  
draft, completed a hectic weekend with a strong first day of 
practice with the Eagles. 
</P>
<P>
	He and the Eagles agreed to terms Friday on a seven-year  
contract worth $54 million, but it wasn't until late Saturday that 
the 32-page contract was approved by the league offices and 
signed. 
</P>
<P>
                             *Patriots    	
</P>
<P>
	Rookie running back Kevin Faulk, being eyed to replace the  
injured Robert Edwards in New England's backfield, got his first 
taste of NFL-style discipline during morning practice. 
</P>
<P>
	After fumbling two punt returns, Faulk received an earful of  
instruction and got some hands-on attention from head coach Pete 
Carroll. The pair spent the next several minutes running through an 
intensive fumble-recovery drill. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, after Faulk dropped a screen pass from backup quarterback  
John Friesz, Carroll ordered the second-round draft choice from LSU 
to the sidelines, where he caught 50 screen passes from rookie 
quarterback Scott Mutryn. 
</P>
<P>
                              *Bills    	
</P>
<P>
	Carrying a dozen fewer pounds than last year, a lean and wary  
Antowain Smith showed up for the start of training camp hopping 
lightly, cutting sharply and running quickly. 
</P>
<P>
	Propelled by rigorous workouts and guided by countless hours of  
studying tape with running backs coach Bishop Harris, Smith is 
determined to prove that Buffalo made the right choice when it 
drafted him in the first round in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
                              *Saints    	
</P>
<P>
	Hall of Fame defensive lineman Randy White was back on a  
football field, grappling with New Orleans players, slapping their 
arms down, stepping around guys 20 years younger and in much better 
condition. 
</P>
<P>
	White and Valentine Espiricueta of Applied Sports Martial Arts  
used a variety of karate moves to show players how to offset the 
grabbing, holding and shoving that goes on in a game. 
</P>
<P>
                              *Giants    	
</P>
<P>
	After missing two seasons with what many felt was a  
career-ending injury to his right eye, Brian Williams, who still 
has trouble seeing when he glances down, is attempting a comeback 
to regain the starting spot he held from 1994-96. 
</P>
<P>
	``Barring another injury somewhere, I think he is the guy,'' new  
line coach Jim McNally said. ``I don't think he is going to 
disappoint us.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             *Dolphins    	
</P>
<P>
	In a spirited intrasquad scrimmage that featured a melee, rookie  
running back Cecil Collins vaulted to the forefront of Miami's 
overcrowded backfield. 
</P>
<P>
	Collins, the Dolphins fifth-round pick whose draft value dropped  
because of several off-field transgressions, rushed for 63 yards on 
13 carries, including a 40-yard touchdown off-tackle burst. 
</P>
<P>
                             *Packers    	
</P>
<P>
	Wide receiver Robert Brooks was missing from practice again amid  
speculation that he could be considering retirement. 
</P>
<P>
	After participating in Green Bay's first full-squad workouts  
Friday, Brooks, 29, was given Saturday off by coach Ray Rhodes 
</P>
<P>
	``My understanding is he's got a couple days to sit back and  
think about it and let Ray or Ron know what he's going to do,'' 
offensive coordinator Sherm Lewis said. 
</P>
<P>
	Brooks has said in the past he would retire if he was not  
completely healthy. 
</P>
<P>
                             *Vikings    	
</P>
<P>
	Minnesota, whose magic carpet ride last season overturned just  
shy of the Super Bowl, reported to training camp eager for 
atonement. 
</P>
<P>
	Some players said they'd use their 30-27 overtime loss to  
Atlanta in the NFC championship to fuel their fire for 1999. Others 
are trying to forget their 15-1 regular season romp that the 
Falcons rendered insignificant. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's the only way to describe it. We want to get that taste  
out of our mouth as soon as we can,'' said running back Robert 
Smith. 
</P>
<P>
                             *Steelers    	
</P>
<P>
	Dermontti Dawson suffered a mild sprain in his left knee and is  
expected to miss the next three to four weeks of the preseason. 
</P>
<P>
	Dawson was injured during a nine-on-seven inside drill less than  
one hour into the second practice session Saturday afternoon at St. 
Vincent College. The severity of the injury was revealed during an 
MRI performed Sunday morning. 
</P>
<P>
	Dawson, who has started 164 straight games for the Steelers  
since late in his rookie year, has opened all 160 in the past 10 
years at center. 
</P>
<P>
                              *Titans    	
</P>
<P>
	If nothing else, Tennessee will know how to get a play off  
without being called for delay of game. 
</P>
<P>
	The Titans were flagged for that penalty more often than any  
other NFL team last season. Coach Jeff Fisher has made fixing that 
tendency a priority in training camp. 
</P>
<P>
	A play clock was installed on the field, and the team worked on  
its timing during two drills in the first full practice of camp. 
</P>
<P>
                            *Buccaneers    	
</P>
<P>
	Tampa Bay will open camp without first-round draft pick Anthony  
McFarland after talks Sunday failed to produce a contract 
agreement. 
</P>
<P>
	General manager Rich McKay said he was ``perplexed and a little  
disappointed,'' that the team had not been able to finalize a deal. 
</P>
<P>
	McKay said talks would continue, but that he was not optimistic  
about having an agreement that would enable McFarland to join the 
team in time for its first practice Monday. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
