<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Heat Wave Death Toll Climbs to 150 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- The death toll from the heat wave that has  
scorched much of the country reached at least 150 as Chicago 
reported a spate of fatalities over the weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	At least 50 people have died in Illinois since the wave began on  
July 19. Chicago Mayor Richard Daley reported 26 of those deaths on 
Saturday, and said an additional 20 deaths may be heat-related and 
were under investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	Meanwhile, New York City ended the hottest July on record.  
</P>
<P>
	Other parts of the East continued to sizzle, too, with  
temperatures in eastern North Carolina soaring into triple digits 
Saturday for a record-setting eighth time this year. The 104-degree 
reading at Raleigh-Durham International Airport broke the 1983 mark 
of seven days over 100 degrees in a year. 
</P>
<P>
	Two cities in Oklahoma, Hobart and Tipton, hit 108.  
Greenville-Spartanburg International Airport in South Carolina hit 
a record high of 104; Louisville, Ky., and Parkersburg, W.Va., were 
at 102; and Columbus, Ohio and Columbus, Ind., both reached 100. 
</P>
<P>
	Philadelphia peaked at 99 degrees on Saturday, making it the  
ninth straight day above 90 degrees. 
</P>
<P>
	In New York, where temperatures had climbed above 90 for the  
last eight days, the thermometer ``only'' hit 88 degrees in Central 
Park. Forecasters were predicting that the first few days of August 
would offer some much-needed relief to the Big Apple. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest fatalities pushed the nation's overall heat-related  
death toll to 150, with many of the victims being found dead in 
homes and apartments without air-conditioning or fans. 
</P>
<P>
	The 50th death in Illinois was in the southern city of  
Metropolis, where a woman who died of heat exhaustion was found in 
the tub. Another death reported Saturday was a North Carolina 
migrant farm worker whose body temperature hit 108 degrees. 
</P>
<P>
	The heat and humidity also may have been a factor in a plane  
crash that killed nine skydivers and a pilot north of Detroit 
moments after take off, federal investigators said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
