<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 09:30:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Chronology of Bush Business Deals </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	1977 -- George W. Bush founds Arbusto Exploration. The Midland,  
Texas-based company primarily put together private partnerships for 
drilling ventures. 
</P>
<P>
	1982 -- Arbusto changes its name to Bush Exploration Co. and goes  
public. 
</P>
<P>
	1984 -- Bush is named director of United Bank of Midland. The  
bank loans the Bush Exploration Co. $372,000. The loan was later 
scrutinized, although a committee of the bank, which did not 
include Bush, approved the loan. It was repaid. 
</P>
<P>
	1984 -- Bush Exploration Co. merges with Spectrum 7 Energy Corp,  
a firm of Cincinnati, Ohio-based investors who backed independent 
oil producers. 
</P>
<P>
	1986 -- Spectrum 7 mergers with Harken Energy Corp. Bush assumes  
consultant role with Harken, which made its mark by buying small 
insolvent companies and making them profitable. 
</P>
<P>
	1989 -- Bush joins board of Tom Brown, an oil exploration company  
based in Midland. 
</P>
<P>
	1989 -- Bush helps put together a deal to buy the Texas Rangers  
baseball club. He buys in as general managing partner for just over 
$600,000. 
</P>
<P>
	1990 -- Harken signs a deal with the government of Bahrain for an  
offshore drilling concession. Critics query whether the lucrative 
contract was made to curry favor with the Bush's father, George 
Bush, who was then president. 
</P>
<P>
	1990 -- Bush joins board of Caterair International Corp., a  
Potomac, Md.-based flight catering company. 
</P>
<P>
	1994 -- Bush elected as Texas governor.  
</P>
<P>
	1998 -- Texas Rangers ballteam is sold to Dallas financier Tom  
Hicks. He receives about $15 million for his part of the deal. 
</P>
<P>
	1999 -- Bush announces he will run for president.  

  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990801.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 18:00:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 9 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Mideast Peace Process May Be In Crisis  
</P>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- A statement from Israeli Prime Minister Ehud  
Barak's office hinted that the Mideast peace process might be 
encountering its first crisis since he took office. Barak said 
today the Palestinians have not been flexible in peace 
negotiations, and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat summoned his top 
negotiators to Cairo for urgent consultations. A Palestinian 
official said a meeting today to discuss implementation of the 
U.S.-brokered Wye accord between Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat 
and his Israeli counterpart, Gilead Sher, ended in ``real crisis.'' 

</P>
<P>
	PBS To Halt Donor List Exchanges  
</P>
<P>
	PASADENA, Calif. (AP) -- PBS stations will halt all exchanges of  
donor lists with partisan groups within a week, but when the 
political fallout for public broadcasting might end is difficult to 
predict, PBS president Ervin S. Duggan said today. Of the 349 
public television stations nationwide, PBS has admitted that as 
many as 30 appear to have engaged in list rentals or exchanges with 
political groups. At issue is whether the list-swapping constitutes 
a violation of federal tax law. 

</P>
<P>
	Lewinsky Hurt in Car Accident  
</P>
<P>
	VENTURA, Calif. (AP) -- Monica Lewinsky suffered scrapes and  
bruises today when her sport utility vehicle overturned on a 
freeway, the California Highway Patrol said. Lewinsky was alone 
when officers found her Ford Explorer on its side on state Highway 
101 about five miles north of town. She was transported to 
Community Memorial Hospital in Ventura, where she was treated and 
released. The cause of the accident remained under investigation. 

</P>
<P>
	Colombian Rebel Army Kills 17  
</P>
<P>
	BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- Hundreds of guerrillas from the nation's  
largest rebel army launched a three-day attack on a police station, 
killing at least 17 people, including nine police officers and four 
children, police said today. Eight other police officers were 
wounded and seven more taken prisoner in the weekend attack by the 
Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia, or FARC. The attack, which 
ended today, was one of the most deadly guerrilla assaults on 
civilians in memory. 

</P>
<P>
	Ivory Coast Elects Candidate  
</P>
<P>
	ABIDJAN, Ivory Coast (AP) -- Thousands of supporters of the Ivory  
Coast's second-largest opposition party elected a former prime 
minister today as their presidential candidate for next year's 
elections. Alassane Dramane Ouattara gave up his position last 
month as a top International Monetary Fund official to lead the 
opposition Rally of the Republicans. He was the party's only 
nominee for its top post, and he was unanimously approved. 

</P>
<P>
	Kosovo Tension High After Explosion  
</P>
<P>
	PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Peacekeepers scrambled to keep a lid  
on simmering ethnic tensions today after a bomb damaged a Serbian 
Orthodox church under construction in Kosovo's capital. The blast 
early today did little damage to the structure, but it further 
undermined the already weak confidence of minority Serbs in the 
ability of the Western alliance's KFOR peacekeeping force to 
protect them from violence they say is committed by ethnic 
Albanians. 

</P>
<P>
	First Lady Explains Husband's Lies  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- First lady Hillary Rodham Clinton, in a magazine  
interview about her marriage, blames her husband's infidelity on a 
desire to please women that can be traced back to his childhood, 
according to The Sunday Times. ``He was so young, barely four, when 
he was scarred by abuse. There was a terrible conflict between his 
mother and grandmother,'' Mrs. Clinton told Talk magazine, 
according to the London-based newspaper, which said it obtained a 
copy of the interview. 

</P>
<P>
	Heat Breaks in Much of Midwest  
</P>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Though temperatures began to drop today across  
the Midwest, the death toll from last week's record-breaking heat 
rose even higher, with another 30 deaths here blamed on the heat 
and humidity. In much of the country, the worst had passed, with 
today's temperatures 10 to 20 degrees cooler across the Great Lakes 
and much of the upper Midwest. Chicago warmed to 81 by early 
afternoon, compared to a high of 104 on Friday. 

</P>
<P>
	Eichelberger Wins Utah Showdown  
</P>
<P>
	PARK CITY, Utah (AP) -- Dave Eichelberger parred the first  
playoff hole today and won the Novell Utah Showdown when Dana 
Quigley's 3-foot putt clipped the cup and rolled past. The victory 
was worth $202,500 to Eichelberger, who three weeks ago won the 
U.S. Senior Open. 

</P>
<P>
	Padres Beat Astros 10-3  
</P>
<P>
	SAN DIEGO (AP) -- Tony Gwynn homered, singled and doubled to move  
within six hits of 3,000 and the San Diego Padres beat Houston 10-3 
today to snap their nine-game losing streak. Gwynn received a 
standing ovation as he was lifted for pinch-runner Damian Jackson 
after doubling leading off the eighth for his 2,994th career hit. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by LINDA KIM  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
