<P>
	The meat will be sent to France mid-August as the centerpiece of  
a marketing drive to persuade the French to buy British beef again. 
</P>
<P>
	Elliot Morley, a deputy Agriculture Minister in the Labor Party  
government, said the ban on sales of beef on the bone would 
continue until independent experts were convinced such meat was 
safe. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are not going to take risks with people's health,'' said  
Morley. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990801.0151 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 09:10:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Book Chronicles Coastline Battle </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RALEIGH, N.C. (AP) -- Sea levels are rising. Sandy beaches, the  
coastal gold standard, are more unstable than ever -- 70 percent are 
eroding. Jetties, seawalls, groins and dredging often only worsen 
beach conditions. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet all along the nation's shoreline, construction of pricey  
beachfront homes is booming, for Americans will not be denied the 
solace of sand and sea. Demographers predict that 80 percent of the 
U.S. population will live within an hour's drive of a coast by next 
year. 
</P>
<P>
	Cornelia Dean describes this alarming scenario in ``Against the  
Tide,'' a 239-page cautionary tale on the pitfalls of tangling with 
nature. The New York Times science editor describes the problems 
clearly in terms laypeople can understand. Her conclusions are 
sobering. 
</P>
<P>
	``In the long run, extensive development cannot coexist with an  
eroding beach -- and most American beaches are eroding,'' Dean 
writes. ``We Americans must reconsider our attitudes toward our 
beaches.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Experts in the field share her thinking. Renowned coastal  
geologist Orrin Pilkey of Duke University has long believed 
erosion-arresting measures are largely self-defeating and only 
encourage even denser coastal development. ``We now have thousands 
more houses at great risk than we had 20 years ago,'' Pilkey said 
recently. 
</P>
<P>
	Coastal areas are constantly being shaped by wind and waves,  
with tricky currents carrying beach-building sediment from one area 
to another. 
</P>
<P>
	Dean writes that currents are amazingly efficient transporters  
of sand. On North Carolina's Outer Banks, 700,000 cubic yards of 
sand per year migrate on currents along any given stretch of beach. 
Crucial details of the process remain a mystery. 
</P>
<P>
	Man's interference in the process with inlet dredging and  
jetties, and with other coastal ``armoring'' such as groins, 
breakwaters and seawalls invariably makes things worse, she says. 
</P>
<P>
	States have come to realize that hardened coastal structures,  
which protect 50 percent of the U.S. shoreline, are decidedly mixed 
blessings. 
</P>
<P>
	Jetties and groins, which extend outward from shore to trap sand  
updrift of them, starve downdrift beaches. Seawalls, which run 
parallel to shorelines, destroy the beaches they are designed to 
protect, Dean writes. 
</P>
<P>
	She describes how a groin field on the east side of a barrier  
island, Westhampton Beach on New York's Long Island, wrecked the 
west end. 
</P>
<P>
	She cites a 1989 study of 108 miles of New Jersey coastline that  
found beaches without stabilizing structures had 180 feet of beach 
and those downdrift of groins or jetties averaged just 60 feet; 
beaches fronting seawalls were only 29 feet wide on the average. 
</P>
<P>
	``At some point, the technological fixes employed to prevent  
shoreline retreat cross the line from resource management to 
vandalism,'' Dean writes. 
</P>
<P>
	New Jersey, notorious for its hardened coastal structures, now  
bars most new ones, as do North Carolina, Maine and South Carolina. 
</P>
<P>
	Along California's armored coastline, the beaches also are  
starving, but for different reasons. Dams and concrete-lined 
waterways prevent much of the sediment that previously fed those 
beaches from reaching the sea, Dean writes. 
</P>
<P>
	With no beach buffer, the cliffs of the Pacific shore are under  
constant attack. Cliffside homeowners are forced to build more 
beach barriers, which, in turn, accelerate erosion somewhere else. 
</P>
<P>
	Beach nourishment has become a common antidote. Dean says  
sometimes it works, but often it doesn't. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some projects, like Miami Beach, have lasted a long time,''  
she writes. ``But many more have washed away far more quickly than 
their designers anticipated.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Either way, beach nourishment is expensive. Folly Beach, S.C.,  
estimates it will cost $116 million to replenish 5.2 miles of 
coastline over 50 years. 
</P>
<P>
	``Against the Tide'' is leavened with spellbinding anecdotes. It  
opens with the disastrous 1900 hurricane in Galveston, Texas, that 
killed nearly 6,000 people. 
</P>
<P>
	There were so many dead, there was no place to bury them. But  
when barges took them to sea, the bodies washed ashore. So they 
were burned in beach bonfires. ``This work, so gruesome that men 
had to be forced at gunpoint to perform it, went on for weeks.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Galveston's leaders vowed it wouldn't happen again. They raised  
the island's elevation and built a seawall. Galveston survived, but 
its beach, once the city's pride, is now gone thanks to the 
seawall. 
</P>
<P>
	The Galveston disaster and Hurricane Andrew's full-scale assault  
in 1992 on southern Florida and Louisiana illustrate the problems 
of coastal development in hurricane-prone areas, Dean writes. 
</P>
<P>
	Her solution is to build back from beachfronts and design homes  
so they might withstand a hurricane -- with reinforced windows, 
heavy-duty roofing nails and metal braces called ``hurricane 
clips'' to attach wall joists to roof beams. 
</P>
<P>
	Dean says beaches take care of themselves when man isn't in the  
picture. 
</P>
<P>
	``The best shore protection is a wide healthy beach,'' she  
writes. ``No amount of rock or concrete can make a beach wider. And 
nature always bats last at the coast.'' 
</P>
<P>
                            	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	``Against the Tide,'' by Cornelia Dean. 239 pages. Columbia  
University Press. $24.95. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
