<HEADLINE> Indians Will Improve Without Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- The way John Hart figures it, the Cleveland  
Indians are on the verge of making several changes to improve their 
roster now that the trading deadline has passed. 
</P>
<P>
	How's that?  
</P>
<P>
	``We have some quality players just about ready to rejoin us,''  
the Indians' general manager said Sunday after failing to make any 
of the anticipated deals. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have Jaret Wright and Kenny Lofton coming back in a couple  
of days and Sandy Alomar in 10 days to two weeks. That should give 
us a lift,'' Hart said. ``We also look for Travis Fryman and Wil 
Cordero to rejoin the team in September.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hart said that he aggressively pursued talks with several teams  
-- but not just for any player. 
</P>
<P>
	``If the right guy was out there for us, we would have done  
something, believe me,'' Hart said. ``We kept looking for that top 
line pitcher.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hart said All-Stars Mike Mussina of Baltimore and Curt Schilling  
of Philadelphia were not available. 
</P>
<P>
	``We into all of this looking for a trade that would have helped  
us regarding our injuries or to bolster us for the postseason,'' 
Hart said. ``We talked to our medical staff first, then projected 
what our team would like like on October 1. We just didn't see any 
players available that would have been better than what we should 
have in October.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hart said he did talk with the Anaheim Angels about acquiring  
left-hander Chuck Finley, but thought the asking price was too 
high. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have developed a lot of good young players the last few  
years and other teams want them,'' Hart said. ``Well, so do we. I 
will say that in some of the deals we have made the last couple of 
years, other clubs have gotten some good talent, but we look for 
the best players to be coming back our way in any deal. Quite 
frankly, Finley's high ERA and lack of success this season were a 
concern to us.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
