<HEADLINE> Starr's Probers Asked About Sex </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Presidential friend Webster Hubbell says  
Kenneth Starr's prosecutors asked him for details about the 
Clintons' sex lives as well as his own. 
</P>
<P>
	In an interview with The New Yorker made public Sunday, Hubbell  
said the prosecutors seemed especially interested in speculation 
about Hillary Rodham Clinton and Vince Foster. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the inquiries were in connection with Starr's  
investigation of Foster's death in 1993 when Foster was working as 
a White House lawyer. 
</P>
<P>
	Three earlier investigations had found Foster killed himself  
with a shot to the head, and Starr's review agreed with that 
conclusion. 
</P>
<P>
	Hubbell did not return a telephone message left at his home  
Sunday. A spokesperson for Starr's office told the magazine that 
the office ``at all time asked relevant and proper questions. A 
professional and thorough suicide investigation always focuses on 
motives.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hubbell, a former associate attorney general, served 16 months  
in prison after pleading guilty to charges of bilking the Rose Law 
Firm, where Mrs. Clinton and Foster worked, and clients out of 
several hundred thousand dollars. 
</P>
<P>
	He now is on a year's probation for a negotiated guilty plea to  
tax evasion. 
</P>
<P>
	Hubbell said prosecutors ``wanted to know about Hillary's sex  
life. About the president's sex life, and mine, too. They 
specifically asked if Hillary and Vince had had an affair.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He added: ``I was surprised. For one thing, I think it's awful  
personal. And I don't think it's anybody's business.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hubbell said prosecutors asked him detailed questions about  
whether he had extramarital sexual relationships with specific 
women. 
</P>
<P>
	The magazine said Hubbell denied any affairs.  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
