<HEADLINE> Texas May Execute 6 in Busy Spurt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HUNTSVILLE, Texas (AP) -- Up to six convicted killers could be  
put to death over two weeks in the busiest spurt of executions in 
Texas in more than two years. The first execution is set for 
Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Texas already accounts for more than a third of all the  
executions in the United States since capital punishment resumed in 
the late 1970s and is closing in on 200 lethal injections since 
convicted murderer Charlie Brooks ushered in the new death penalty 
era in the state in 1982. 
</P>
<P>
	The Texas count now stands at 180, including 16 this year.  
</P>
<P>
	The six convicted killers set to die this month are all longtime  
death row inmates whose confinements range from more than 11 years 
to more than 18 years. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every young man on death row should give thanks to God when  
they get an execution date,'' inmate Ricky Blackmon said in a 
recent interview with The Associated Press. ``If they wanted to 
punish me, that would be a life sentence. They're giving me a way 
out. I'm thanking God for it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Blackmon, 41, is set to die Wednesday for the robbery-slaying of  
a man stabbed and slashed with a homemade medieval-style sword in 
1987. All his appeals are exhausted, but any of those on Death Row 
could have their executions stayed. 
</P>
<P>
	Another six inmates already are on the execution schedule for  
September and October. It's possible this year could challenge the 
record of 37 prisoners put to death in 1997. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
