<HEADLINE> Russian Says Country Needs Food Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOSCOW (AP) -- A Russian grain official has called on the  
government to appeal to the West for food aid now, even before the 
1999 harvest is in, the Interfax news agency reported Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Leonid Chesinsky, the president of the Roskhlebprodukt bakery  
company, said that corporate grain experts expect this year's 
harvest, which has been blighted by drought, would bring just 50-55 
million tons. That is about 15-20 tons short of demand. 
</P>
<P>
	He said that the state would have to import some 14-15 million  
tons of grain just for human bread consumption. 
</P>
<P>
	``But if the government intends to revive livestock and poultry  
breeding in this country, grain imports must far exceed this 
figure,'' Interfax quoted him as saying. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year's poor grain harvest of 48 million tons forced the  
government to ask for food aid from the United States and the 
European Union. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
