<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jets Try To Plug Holes in Line </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. (AP) -- The New York Jets, surprised when veteran  
offensive lineman Erik Norgard walked out of camp a day ago, filled 
that roster spot Sunday with free-agent guard Ian Beckles. 
</P>
<P>
	The 6-foot-1, 305-pound Beckles, a 10-year veteran, is expected  
to step in immediately as the starter at right guard ahead of 
second-round draft pick Randy Thomas of Mississippi State. 
</P>
<P>
	Beckles, a former Philadelphia Eagles starter, was given a  
one-year contract. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think I have some good years left in me,'' said Beckles, 32.  
``I'm coming here to start. I've never come off the bench before. 
If I am used as a backup, it means I didn't do my job.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Jets' offensive line has been a major focal point for coach  
Bill Parcells during the offseason. After waiving left guard Todd 
Burger and allowing right guard Matt O'Dwyer to leave as a free 
agent, Parcells signed Norgard, a former Oilers starter, to a 
three-year, $2.4 million deal. Parcells also took three guards in 
this year's draft. 
</P>
<P>
	Beckles, who has started 122 of his 127 career games, played for  
Tampa Bay from 1990-96 and Philadelphia the past two seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's a veteran and we're going to put him in there and see  
what he can do. We had him in during the offseason to talk to him. 
He's going to have to come in and show me that he can do it,'' 
Parcells said. 
</P>
<P>
	Second-year player Doug Karczewski and rookie David Loverne, a  
third-round selection, are battling for the starting left guard 
position. 
</P>
<P>
	Following Saturday's morning practice, Norgard notified Parcells  
that he had chosen to give up football. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
