<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 7 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	White House Touts Welfare Changes  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- All 50 states have moved the required number  
of people from welfare to work, the White House said today, noting 
that 35 percent of the nation's welfare recipients held jobs in 
1998. The president plans to promote those numbers on Tuesday at a 
welfare-to-work conference in Chicago, and use them to make the 
case for Congress to provide funding for services, such as child 
care, to aid the welfare-to-work transition. 

</P>
<P>
	First Lady Explains Husband's Lies  
</P>
<P>
	LONDON (AP) -- First lady Hillary Rodham Clinton, in a magazine  
interview about her marriage, blames her husband's infidelity on a 
desire to please women that can be traced back to his childhood, 
according to The Sunday Times. ``He was so young, barely four, when 
he was scarred by abuse. There was a terrible conflict between his 
mother and grandmother,'' Mrs. Clinton told Talk magazine, 
according to the London-based newspaper, which said it obtained a 
copy of the interview. 

</P>
<P>
	Barak Reportedly To Delay Accord  
</P>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- Prime Minister Ehud Barak told his Cabinet  
today that implementation of parts of a suspended Mideast peace 
accord might begin within a month, a cabinet statement said. The 
statement did not specify when withdrawals from the West Bank would 
begin, but a Barak spokesman said the ``physical implementation'' 
of the agreement would begin Oct. 1. More delays would likely anger 
the Palestinians, who have called for immediate implementation of 
the U.S.-brokered Wye River accord. 

</P>
<P>
	Rains in S. Korea Kill At Least 10  
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- Rescue workers in dinghies and  
helicopters plucked stranded residents from flooded homes today 
after two days of deadly torrential rains left at least 10 people 
dead and forced more than 11,380 to flee. The downpours caused the 
flooding of homes between the South Korean capital of Seoul and the 
border with North Korea. Two people were missing. 

</P>
<P>
	3 Kids Killed Playing With Ammo  
</P>
<P>
	ELAZIG, Turkey (AP) -- Three children died today in central  
Turkey when a live artillery shell they were playing with exploded, 
the Anatolia news agency said. Another five children were injured. 
The children had strayed onto a field used by Turkey's military for 
live-fire exercises and were using stones to crack walnuts on the 
shell, the news agency said. 

</P>
<P>
	Couple Just Missed Fateful Flight  
</P>
<P>
	COTTRELLVILLE TOWNSHIP, Mich. (AP) -- Lateness saved the lives of  
skydivers Bob and Caroline Johnson who just missed joining their 
fellow parachutists aboard a flight that crashed, killing 10. The 
couple showed up late for yesterday's first flight of the 1967 
Beech King Air 65A-90 which veered sharply shortly after takeoff 
and plummeted into a hayfield, exploding into a ball of fire. 

</P>
<P>
	Cops Killed in Colombia Attack  
</P>
<P>
	BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- Hundreds of leftist rebels launched a  
three-day attack on a police station with homemade missiles and 
automatic weapons, killing at least nine officers and destroying 
nearby homes and businesses, police said today. Eight police were 
wounded, and 11 more feared taken prisoner in the weekend attack, 
which ended today. Leftist Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia 
on Friday began ravaging the small town of Narino, 100 miles 
northwest of Bogota in the state of Antioquia. 

</P>
<P>
	Webb Wins du Maurier Classic  
</P>
<P>
	PRIDDIS, Alberta (AP) -- Karrie Webb staged a dramatic comeback  
on the back nine of Priddis Greens today for a 6-under 66 to win 
the du Maurier Classic, her first major championship. Starting the 
final round five strokes back, Webb followed crucial par saves with 
birdies on three of the last four holes to finish at 11-under 277 
for a two-stroke victory over Laura Davies. Juli Inkster's bid to 
win her third-straight major championship and a berth in the LPGA 
Hall of Fame never materialized. 

</P>
<P>
	Davenport Wins at Bank of the West  
</P>
<P>
	STANFORD, Calif. (AP) -- Lindsay Davenport used power to control  
the match against Venus Williams and win 7-6 (7-1), 6-2 today in 
the final of the Bank of the West Classic for the second-straight 
year. Davenport, who has won eight of nine matches against 
Williams, had defeated her 6-4, 5-7, 6-4 in this tournament's final 
last year. Davenport used that win as a springboard toward the U.S. 
Open title and the No. 1 ranking. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by LINDA KIM  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
