<DATE_TIME> 1999-08-01 21:10:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	70 Killed in India Explosion  
</P>
<P>
	NEW DELHI, India (AP) -- The Press Trust of India news agency  
reported that a major explosion rocked a railroad station in 
eastern India early Monday, killing at least 70 passengers and 
injuring 135. The news agency said the blast ripped five coaches of 
a stationary train and six coaches of another train that was 
passing through Gaisan railroad station. 

</P>
<P>
	Barak Calls Palestinians Inflexible  
</P>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak said Sunday  
Palestinians have not been flexible in peace negotiations, and 
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat summoned his top negotiators to 
Cairo for urgent consultations. A Palestinian official said a 
meeting Sunday to discuss implementation of the U.S.-brokered Wye 
accord between Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat and his Israeli 
counterpart, Gilead Sher, ended in ``real crisis.'' 

</P>
<P>
	Rains in S.Korea Kill At Least 12  
</P>
<P>
	SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- Rescue workers in dinghies and  
helicopters plucked stranded residents from flooded homes after 
deadly torrential rains. At least 12 were reported dead Monday in 
South Korea. Nearly 7,000 houses were flooded and at least 15,000 
people fled their homes, many taking shelter in schools and 
government buildings where they slept on mats and ate donated rice 
and soup. Towns and villages were swamped by muddy floodwaters 
caused by up to 23 inches of rain. 

</P>
<P>
	Colombian Rebel Army Kills 17  
</P>
<P>
	BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- Police said Sunday that hundreds of  
guerrillas from the nation's largest rebel army launched a 
three-day attack on a police station, killing at least 17 people, 
including nine police officers and four children. Eight other 
police officers were wounded and seven more taken prisoner in the 
weekend attack by the Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia. The 
attack, which ended Sunday, was one of the most deadly guerrilla 
assaults on civilians in memory. The rebel barrage was said to have 
destroyed 30 homes, the mayor's office, a bank and a school. 

</P>
<P>
	Two Earthquakes Shake Aleutians  
</P>
<P>
	PALMER, Alaska (AP) -- Two earthquakes shook the Aleutian Islands  
Sunday, but there were no reports of damage or injuries. The first, 
a moderate 5.5 quake, jolted Adak at 4:48 a.m. The quake was 
centered about 30 miles southeast of Adak, about halfway down the 
island chain, and was felt strongly on the island. The second was a 
magnitude 4.9 quake, which shook Atka at 12:11 p.m. It was centered 
about 60 miles southeast of Atka. 

</P>
<P>
	PBS To Halt Donor List Exchanges  
</P>
<P>
	PASADENA, Calif. (AP) -- PBS President Ervin S. Duggan said  
Sunday stations will halt all exchanges of donor lists with 
partisan groups within a week, but when the political fallout for 
public broadcasting might end is difficult to predict. Of the 349 
public television stations nationwide, PBS has admitted that 30 
appear to have engaged in list rentals or exchanges with political 
groups. At issue is whether the list-swapping constitutes a 
violation of federal tax law. Tax experts have said that such 
exchanges would not be a violation as long as all political parties 
receive equal access to the lists. 

</P>
<P>
	Japan Stocks Fall  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- The Nikkei shed 110.86 points to 17,751.00 in early  
trading Monday. On Friday, the average closed down 8.06 points. In 
New York on Friday, the Dow industrials slid for a second-straight 
session, losing 136.14 points. 

</P>
<P>
	Red Sox Beat Yankees 5-4  
</P>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Bret Saberhagen stopped his three-game winless  
streak and Orlando Hernandez suffered his first loss in 46 days as 
the Boston Red Sox beat the New York Yankees 5-4 Sunday night. 
Saberhagen (7-4) retired the last 14 batters he faced before 
reliever Tim Wakefield nearly blew the game 

</P>
<P>
	Sampras Wins Mercedes-Benz Cup  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Pete Sampras overpowered Andre Agassi 7-6  
(7-3), 7-6 (7-1) to win the championship of the Mercedes-Benz Cup 
at the Los Angeles Tennis Center. The match was as tight as could 
be, except for the tiebreakers, where Sampras won 14 of the 18 
points contested. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by LINDA KIM  
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
