<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Patriots' Faulk Gets Rookie Initiation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SMITHFIELD, R.I. (AP) -- Welcome to the NFL, Kevin Faulk.  
</P>
<P>
	The rookie running back, being eyed to replace the injured  
Robert Edwards in the New England Patriots' backfield this season, 
got his first taste of NFL-style discipline during Sunday morning's 
practice at Bryant College. 
</P>
<P>
	After fumbling two punt returns, Faulk received an earful of  
instruction and got some hands-on attention from head coach Pete 
Carroll. The pair spent the next several minutes running through an 
intensive fumble-recovery drill, with Carroll rolling the ball on 
the ground and standing over Faulk to make sure he recovered it 
properly. 
</P>
<P>
	Then, after Faulk dropped a screen pass from backup quarterback  
John Friesz, Carroll ordered the second-round draft choice from 
Louisiana State to the sidelines, where he caught 50 screen passes 
from rookie quarterback Scott Mutryn. 
</P>
<P>
	Faulk didn't object to the extra attention.  
</P>
<P>
	``If a coach doesn't get on a player, he's not being a coach,''  
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Carroll, too, said the unrelenting pressure was a normal part of  
rookie initiation. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's got to understand how important this job is and the  
responsibility that the running back who takes this spot has on his 
shoulders,'' Carroll said. ``I look for every opportunity to make 
that point to him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Patriots were thrust into the search for another starting  
running back when Edwards, last year's outstanding rookie, suffered 
a career-threatening injury to his left knee in February while 
participating in a Pro Bowl weekend touch football game for rookies 
in Honolulu. 
</P>
<P>
	After the Patriots failed in attempts to make trades for the  
rights to draft highly regarded collegians Ricky Williams and 
Edgerrin James, they opted to take Faulk with the 46th overall 
selection. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite speculation that the 5-foot-8, 197-pounder might be too  
small, Carroll has maintained he thinks Faulk has ``an air about 
him and a confidence'' that will help him get the job done. But 
Carroll added that he has to see more. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's just getting started,'' Carroll said. ``He's got some  
toughness about him. How tough? We'll just have to wait and see.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Patriots also have signed former Indianapolis backup Lamont  
Warren, and intend to give last year's third-down back, Derrick 
Cullors, a chance to compete for the starting job. 
</P>
<P>
	Faulk said he welcomes the competition.  
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not going to say I can come in right away and play, but  
I'm going to try,'' he said. ``If you start putting too much 
pressure on yourself, you tend to overdo it. You just have to relax 
and let everything take care of itself.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Carroll said he will use all of the Patriots' four preseason  
games to let the tailback search play itself out. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not overanxious to make a quick decision,'' he said.  
``There's no point in doing that. We'll take all the information 
and wait. Guys will get their featured opportunities.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
