<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gun Control Advocates Regroup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ATLANTA (AP) -- Last spring's Colorado school massacre gave gun  
control advocates much to further their agenda. They had a villain: 
the TEC-DC-9, a banned, cheap semiautomatic pistol favored by drug 
dealers. They had a regulatory problem: lax sales rules at gun 
shows. 
</P>
<P>
	But Mark O. Barton's shooting spree last week in Atlanta, which  
took nine lives, is another story. 
</P>
<P>
	Half the nation's police officers carry the 9 mm Glock-19  
semiautomatic pistol assembled a dozen miles from the brokerage 
firms where Barton killed six of his victims. His other weapon, a 
Colt .45 pistol, is the gun Tom Hanks aims at a tank in the final 
scene of ``Saving Private Ryan'' and the gun Sgt. Alvin C. York 
used to single-handedly capture 132 Germans during World War I. 
</P>
<P>
	While the Atlanta killings have energized gun control advocates,  
they provide few clear examples of the narrow issues gun control 
advocates have recently pursued. 
</P>
<P>
	Child safety locks wouldn't have deterred Barton. Police had no  
evidence he got his guns illegally, or bought them at a gun show 
where sales rules are lax. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest slayings strip the debate to the most basic question  
-- should handguns be banned entirely, said Josh Sugarman, executive 
director of the Washington-based Violence Policy Center. 
</P>
<P>
	``Until we start talking about banning handguns in this country,  
this is America's future. We'll have shootings in schools, in 
office buildings, in malls,'' Sugarman said. ``In America, wherever 
you're amid a large concentration of people, you're at risk.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Friday, a group of Colorado students stood at the site of the  
May massacre at Columbine High School to renew their call for 
stronger curbs on handgun ownership. 
</P>
<P>
	Atlanta and Columbine ``taught us all that violence can happen  
everywhere, not just in the inner city, not just by hardened 
criminals,'' said Ben Gelt, a recent Denver high school graduate 
who organized student gun control advocates following the Littleton 
shootings. 
</P>
<P>
	A spokesman for the National Rifle Association, Bill Powers,  
criticized efforts to ``score political points off of a tragedy'' 
and said he doesn't expect the Atlanta shootings to lead to 
significant changes in gun law. 
</P>
<P>
	``If they want to come out and debate a total handgun ban in  
America, that's a debate they'll lose with the American people,'' 
Powers said. 
</P>
<P>
	Glock Inc. and Colt's Manufacturing Company Inc. are among the  
dozens of gun makers named in lawsuits filed by Atlanta, 15 other 
cities and three counties since November. The suits allege the gun 
makers recklessly or unfairly put guns in the hands of criminals. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet unlike the low-cost, high-powered assault weapons used in  
Littleton and elsewhere, the guns used in Atlanta have drawn 
comparatively little criticism. 
</P>
<P>
	``If you believe the manufacture and sale of guns is at all  
legitimate, certainly the Colt .45 and the Glock would meet the 
description of acceptable weapons,'' conceded Naomi Paiss, a 
spokeswoman for Handgun Control Inc., a Washington group that 
lobbies for gun control. 
</P>
<P>
	The Colt .45 was used by the U.S. military from 1911 until the  
1980s, when it was phased out in favor of a Beretta. Police 
officers like the Austrian-designed Glock 9 mm for its reliability, 
ease of maintenance and light weight. 
</P>
<P>
	Both sell for $500 to $550, although custom models can cost  
more. 
</P>
<P>
	The Glock drew unwanted attention in the film ``Die Hard 2''  
when Bruce Willis' character mistakenly said the gun was 
undetectable to metal detectors because it's made entirely of 
plastic. The barrel and other parts actually are metal, notes Bob 
Glass, a gun enthusiast and publisher of the magazine The Partisan 
who has run a Glock through a metal detector. 
</P>
<P>
	``Believe me, it showed up clear as day,'' Glass said.  
</P>
<P>
	Police said a duffel bag in Barton's van also contained a  
.25-caliber Raven semiautomatic pistol and a .22-caliber Harrington 
&AMP; Richardson revolver, both of which he apparently bought legally 
in pawn shops. They weren't used in the killings. 
</P>
<P>
	The Atlanta shootings have drawn attention to two narrow  
gun-control issues: gun sales to people with psychological 
problems, and large-capacity ammunition clips. 
</P>
<P>
	The Glock can hold 16 bullets. The federal Brady bill of 1994  
banned the manufacture of clips holding more than 10 bullets, but 
allowed those already on the market to be owned and resold. 
Congress has shown little interest in broadening the ban. 
</P>
<P>
	Paiss, of Handgun Control, questioned whether psychological  
traits should bar some from owning guns. 
</P>
<P>
	Glock lawyer Paul Jannuzzo said he'd support psychological  
restrictions if there was a way of doing it. But privacy advocates 
would likely oppose opening medical records to gun vendors. 
</P>
<P>
	And there's little evidence a psychologically based ban would  
have affected Barton. Douglas County District Attorney David McDade 
recalled that a psychologist who once examined Barton after a child 
abuse complaint considered him capable of homicide. 
</P>
<P>
	However, in his written report on Barton, the psychologist  
dismissed the possibility of sexual abuse and didn't mention his 
suspicions about Barton's propensity for violence, McDade and child 
welfare officials said. 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
