<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> MBNA Mid-Atlantic 200 Notebook </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DOVER, Del. (AP) -- Moments after rookie Scott Harrington got out  
of his car following the MBNA Mid-Atlantic 200 on Sunday, Eddie 
Cheever and Robbie Unser accosted him as he was seated on the pit 
wall. 
</P>
<P>
	Owner-driver Cheever, who crashed early in the race, and Unser,  
who drives for him, were unhappy with the tactics of Harrington. 
Witnesses said Cheever grabbed Harrington -- still recovering from a 
broken leg -- by the collar with both hands and screamed obscenities 
in his face. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't think I even played a role in Eddie's accident,'' said  
Harrington, who finished fifth in the race at Dover Downs 
International Speedway. ``I'm sorry if they're upset, but I think 
if they watch the video they'll feel differently.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Unser also joined the dispute, although no punches were thrown  
before others stepped in. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is just the beginning,'' witnesses said he shouted at  
Harrington. 
</P>
<P>
	Later, in an interview, race winner Greg Ray, who crashed with  
Cheever in Dover last year, said the 1998 Indianapolis 500 champion 
``just can't let it go.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cheever has been openly hostile toward Ray, who complimented  
Harrington for his driving. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm disappointed for their behavior,'' Harrington said of  
Cheever and Unser. ``Their lack of professionalism is a bad 
reflection not only on them but also on the series.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Neither Cheever, Unser nor the IRL had any immediate comment on  
the situation. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *CROWD DOWN:* When it became obvious that oppressive heat and  
humidity would keep its grip on the East Coast all weekend, Indy 
Racing League officials figured attendance would be down for their 
event at Dover Downs International Speedway. 
</P>
<P>
	They were right. It fell from about 25,000 in 1998 -- for the  
first Indy-car race in 29 years on the Monster Mile -- to an 
estimated 15,000 Sunday for the MBNA Mid-Atlantic 200. 
</P>
<P>
	``We depend on walkup business at these larger NASCAR tracks,  
and today the hot weather did not help that,'' said IRL vice 
president Fred Nation. ``But we're very happy that the track does 
everything it can to promote these races.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hot and humid are the operative words for midsummer in Dover,  
something Nation realizes will not change. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have another year on the contract with Dover Downs, and we  
hope to be working on a date, and hope things will get better with 
more familiarity in the area for open-wheel racing,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Nation said a change in the date would be considered for Dover,  
but added that decisions on the 2000 IRL schedule won't be made for 
about three months. 
</P>
<P>
	Oppressive heat is a problem in many areas during the summer.  
Last week, in Brooklyn, Mich., only about 50,000 attended the U.S. 
500, filling less than half the seats at Michigan Speedway for one 
of CART's top races. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *THE MONSTER MILE:* Running on high-banked ovals is nothing new  
to drivers in the Indy Racing League. But the 24 degrees of banking 
on what they call The Monster Mile are tighter and narrower than 
those on other tracks. 
</P>
<P>
	``At times, it felt like the steering wheel weighed 300  
pounds,'' Tyce Carlson said. 
</P>
<P>
	Jeff Ward has been among those with the most respect for the  
track, used Sunday for just the second time by the IRL cars in the 
MBNA Mid-Atlantic 200. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was just a matter of survival,'' Ward said.  
</P>
<P>
	He got no argument from Billy Boat, who wound up fourth in the  
race won by Greg Ray. 
</P>
<P>
	``This place is a physical as any track that I've run a  
30-lapper on,'' Boat said. ``But you have to run 200 laps here.'' 
  	   	
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
